## Chapter 1 (continued): The Dream of Inca Gold

### The Human Cost of Potosí

- Miners died from mercury fumes (the **patio process**: ore ground
  into amalgam with mercury, then heated to burn it off), rock falls,
  and 700-foot descents carrying ore sacks on their backs
- **Domingo de Santo Tomás** called Potosí "a mouth of hell, into
  which a great mass of people enter every year and are sacrificed
  by the greed of the Spaniards to their 'god'"
- **Rodrigo de Loaisa**: "if twenty healthy Indians enter on Monday,
  half may emerge crippled on Saturday"

> 'Every peso coin minted in Potosí has cost the life of ten Indians
> who have died in the depths of the mines.'
> — Fray Antonio de la Calancha, 1638

- As indigenous workforce was depleted, thousands of African slaves
  imported as "human mules"
- Between 1556 and 1783, Cerro Rico yielded **45,000 tons of pure
  silver**; Potosí peaked at 160,000–200,000 people — larger than
  most European cities; *Valer un potosí* = Spanish for "to be
  worth a fortune"

### The Three Functions of Money

- Conventional definition: **medium of exchange** (eliminates
  barter inefficiency); **unit of account** (enables valuation);
  **store of value** (enables transactions across time and distance)
- To perform optimally: available, affordable, durable, fungible,
  portable, reliable
- Earliest coins: ~600 BC, **Lydian** ovular coins of electrum
  (gold-silver alloy) found at Temple of Artemis, Ephesus — bore a
  lion's head; forerunners of Athenian **tetradrachm**
- Roman coinage: **aureus** (gold), **denarius** (silver),
  **sestertius** (bronze) — ranked by metal scarcity; bore the
  emperor's head
- China: standardized bronze coin introduced 221 BC by first Emperor,
  **Qin Shihuangdi**
- Key pattern: precious-metal coins associated with sovereigns who
  **monopolized minting as a revenue source**

### Medieval Silver Shortage

- Roman coinage system outlived the empire — prices still quoted in
  silver denarii in **Charlemagne**'s time (768–814 AD)
- By 800, chronic silver shortage in Western Europe; metal drained
  eastward to the more commercially advanced **Islamic Empire**
- In Charlemagne's time 24 denarii bought a Carolingian cow; peppers
  and squirrel skins served as substitute currency; *pecunia* came
  to mean land rather than money
- Europe's two solutions: (1) export labour/goods to Baghdad/Cordoba
  for silver; (2) plunder via war on the Muslim world
- **Contrarian claim**: The Crusades were as much about overcoming
  Europe's monetary shortage as about religious conversion

### The "Big Problem of Small Change"

- Medieval governments failed to establish stable relationships
  between coins of different metals → smaller denominations subject
  to recurrent shortages AND debasement
- Spanish New World silver (Potosí + Zacatecas, Mexico) appeared to
  break this centuries-old constraint
- Convoys of up to 100 ships transported **170 tons of silver/year**
  across the Atlantic to Seville; a fifth reserved for the crown =
  **44% of total royal expenditure** at peak (late 16th century)
- The Spanish **"piece of eight"** (based on the German *thaler*,
  hence "dollar") became the **world's first truly global currency**
  — financed Spain's European wars and rapidly expanding Asia trade

### The Price Revolution and the Resource Curse

- Spain's silver paradox: the more they mined, the poorer they became
  in real terms
- **"Price revolution"** 1540s–1640s: cost of food (flat for 300
  years) rose markedly across all of Europe; English cost of living
  rose **sevenfold** in the period (~2% annual inflation, but
  revolutionary by medieval standards)
- Within Spain: silver acted as a **resource curse** — like Arabian
  oil or Nigerian oil in our era — removing incentives for productive
  activity, strengthening rent-seeking autocrats (Charles V and
  Philip II) at the expense of the Cortes (representative assembly)
- Core insight: **"The value of precious metal is not absolute.
  Money is worth only what someone else is willing to give you for
  it."** Monetary expansion merely makes prices higher — it does
  not make society richer

### Money as Trust, Not Metal

- No historical necessity that money = metal; this was contingent,
  not inevitable
- **Ancient Mesopotamia** (~5,000 years ago): clay tokens recorded
  transactions in barley, wool, silver; debts were transferable
  ("pay the bearer" not a named creditor)
- Key observation: **when humans first wrote things down, they did
  so not for history, poetry, or philosophy — but to do business**
- Clay tablet from Sippar (modern Tell Abu Habbah, Iraq), reign of
  King **Ammi-ditana** (1683–1647 BC): bearer to receive specific
  barley at harvest; successor King **Ammi-saduqa**: bearer to
  receive silver at end of journey
- Modern **banknotes** (originated in 7th-century China) are just
  promissory notes — like Babylonian clay tablets, four millennia
  later
- Bank of England note: "I promise to pay the bearer on demand the
  sum of..."
- US $10 bill: "In God We Trust" but you are really trusting
  Alexander Hamilton's successor at the Treasury + the Fed Chairman
  not to repeat Spain's error and manufacture so many dollars they
  become worthless
- **Cash in hands of ordinary Americans = only 11% of M2**
  (monetary measure); most money is now invisible/electronic
- Ferguson's thesis: **"Money is not metal. It is trust inscribed."**
  Medium is irrelevant — silver, clay, paper, LCD — anything can
  serve (cowrie shells, Yap stone discs)

### Origins of Credit: Ancient Babylon

- Core financial relationship is between **lender and borrower**
- Babylonian lending system was sophisticated:
  - Debts transferable ("pay the bearer")
  - Clay receipts issued to those depositing grain at temples/palaces
  - Interest rates up to **20 per cent**; mathematical exercises from
    **Hammurabi**'s reign (1792–1750 BC) show compound interest
    on long-term loans
  - Laws of Hammurabi prescribed **debt forgiveness every 3 years**
    — but didn't deter lending, as the long-term trend was expansion
  - The root of "credit" is *credo* — Latin for "I believe"
- By 6th century BC, Babylonian family firm **Egibi** had emerged
  as powerful landowners and lenders; commercial interests from
  Uruk to Persia; thrived for **five generations**
- Caveat: Babylonian loans were mostly royal/religious storehouses
  advancing goods — not modern credit creation. But an essential
  beginning.

