## The Evolution of Banking (section within Chapter 1)

### Three 17th-Century Innovations

**1. Amsterdam Exchange Bank (*Wisselbank*), 1609**
- Created to resolve problems of 14 different mints and copious foreign coins
  circulating in the United Provinces
- Pioneered **cheques and direct debits** by allowing merchants to hold
  accounts in a standardized currency; payments made by debiting/crediting
  accounts — no physical coin needed
- Limitation: maintained near **100% reserve ratio** (deposits of 19M florins
  in 1760, metallic reserve over 16M) — virtually immune to bank runs but
  incapable of **credit creation**

**2. Swedish Riksbank, 1656**
- Performed Wisselbank functions AND was designed as a ***Lanebank*** —
  it lent as well as facilitated payments
- Pioneered **fractional reserve banking**: lent amounts in excess of metallic
  reserve, exploiting the fact that depositors are highly unlikely to
  withdraw *en masse*
- Balance sheet: liabilities = deposits + reserve (no interest earned);
  assets = loans (interest collected)

**3. Bank of England, 1694**
- Created primarily to assist **war finance** — government debt converted
  into bank shares
- From 1709: only bank allowed to operate on **joint-stock** basis
- From 1742: partial monopoly on **banknote** issue — promissory notes not
  bearing interest, facilitating payments without current accounts

### The Money Multiplier (Harvard MBA Game)
- Central bank pays professor $100 → deposited at Bank 1
- Bank 1 (10% reserve rule) keeps $10, lends $90 → deposited at Bank 2
- Bank 2 keeps $9, lends $81 → and so on
- Result: **M0** (monetary base) = $100; **M1** (narrow money) = $271
  after three rounds — illustrates how fractional reserve banking
  **creates credit and hence money**
- The reverse: professor calls in $100 → **bank run domino** collapses
  M1 as fast as it expanded; reveals the **liquidity** problem at the heart
  of banking

### Money Supply Definitions
- **M0**: monetary base = total central bank liabilities (cash + bank reserves)
- **M1**: narrow money = cash in circulation + demand/sight deposits
- **M2**: adds savings accounts, money market deposits, CDs
- **M3**: broadest — includes eurodollar deposits, repo agreements
- Key shift: money ceased to mean precious metal dug up and minted; it became
  the sum total of banks' liabilities. **Credit** = total of banks' assets
  (loans)
- Core bank function evolved to: **information gathering and risk management**;
  profit = maximizing spread between cost of liabilities and earnings on assets
  without reducing reserves to the point of a run

### Spain's Paradox
- Despite controlling the silver of **Potosí**, Spain **failed** to develop
  a sophisticated banking system
- Relied on Antwerp merchants for short-term cash advances against future
  silver deliveries — never grasped that money is about **credit, not metal**
- Spanish crown defaulted on all or part of its debt **14 times** between
  1557 and 1696

> "In the modern world, power would go to the bankers, not the bankrupts."
> — Ferguson

### 19th-Century British Banking Evolution
- **Adam Smith** (1776): "The judicious operation of banking... provides...
  a sort of waggon-way through the air"
- Post-*Wealth of Nations* explosion of bank types: bill-discounting banks,
  merchant banks (**Barings**), country banks
- **Bank of England** gradually assumed public functions — clearing hub,
  monopoly on note issue reaffirmed 1826
- **Peel's Bank Charter Act (1844)**: split Bank into banking dept and
  issue dept; fiduciary note issue capped — proved too rigid; Act suspended
  in crises of 1847, 1857, 1866
- **Walter Bagehot** (*The Economist*), after Overend Gurney collapse 1866:
  reformulated Bank's role as **"lender of last resort"** — lend freely at
  a penalty rate to combat liquidity crises
- **Baron Overstone** encapsulated the old view: "Precious Metals alone are
  money... Paper notes are money because they are representations of Metallic
  Money." Had this held, UK growth would have been choked off
- After 1858 joint-stock restrictions lifted → consolidation into big
  commercial banks: **London & Westminster** (1833), **National Provincial**
  (1834), **Lloyds** (1884), **Barclays** (1896)
- By eve of WWI: British bank deposits = £1.2 billion vs. banknote circulation
  of only £45.5 million — "Money was now primarily inside banks, out of sight"
- Country banks declined from 755 (1809) to 17 (1913)

### Central Banking Goes Global
- **Banque de France** 1800, **German Reichsbank** 1875, **Bank of Japan**
  1882, **Swiss National Bank** 1907

### US Banking: The Free Banking Experiment
- Political aversion to powerful financiers → first and second **Banks of
  the United States** both killed; **Federal Reserve** not created until 1913
- **National Bank Act 1864**: low barriers to entry, low capital requirements
- Banks surged from <12,000 (1899) to >30,000 (peak 1922)
- Under-capitalized banks → regular panics; Great Depression saw Federal
  Reserve **exacerbate** rather than mitigate the banking crisis
- **Deposit insurance (1933)** reduced bank run vulnerability
- Interstate banking not legal until **Maine 1976**; bank count fell below
  3,600 only after 1993 (post-S&L crisis)

### The Gold Standard's Fall
- **John Maynard Keynes** (1924): gold standard is a "barbarous relic"
- Gold standard advantages: exchange rate stability, low transaction costs,
  inflation anchor, lower borrowing costs
- Fatal flaw: impossible trinity — currency peg forces choice between
  free capital movements and independent monetary policy; can transmit
  deflation and financial crises
- Last vestige removed **15 August 1971** when **President Nixon** closed
  the gold "window" — centuries-old link between money and precious metal
  broken
- Since then: dollar's purchasing power (vs. CPI) has fallen **87%**;
  average annual inflation >4% — twice the rate from the Potosí silver
  revolution; $1,000 in gold in 1970 = 26.6 oz → worth ~$26,596 by 2008

