## Bankrupt Nation (section within Chapter 1)

### Memphis as Case Study in Credit Risk
- Ferguson visits **Memphis, Tennessee** (2007) — 1–2 million US bankruptcy
  cases per year, disproportionately in Tennessee
- Street-level ecosystem of easy credit: car-title loans, second-mortgage
  companies, cheque-cashing shops at 200% interest, pawnshops, Rent-A-Center,
  a Plasma Center ($55 per blood donation)
- "Modern Memphis gives a whole new meaning to 'bled dry'"

### American Bankruptcy as a Right
- No debtors' prisons in early 19th-century US (while English debtors
  languished in jail for years)
- Since 1898: every American can file **Chapter VII** (liquidation) or
  **Chapter XIII** (voluntary reorganization)
- Theory: law encourages entrepreneurship — failed entrepreneurs like
  **John Henry Heinz**, **Phineas Barnum**, **Henry Ford** eventually
  succeeded after bankruptcy
- Reality check: 98% of Memphis filings are **non-business** — ordinary
  individuals unable to pay, especially **medical bills** from lack of
  health insurance
- 2007 US consumer debt: **$2.5 trillion** (record); in 1959 consumer debt
  was 16% of disposable income — now **24%**

### The Broader Implication
- Breaking the link between money creation and a metallic anchor unleashed
  **unprecedented monetary expansion**
- Broad money / GDP ratio rose from ~70% (pre-1971 gold window) to >100%
  by 2005; eurozone from 60% (1990) to 90%
- European bank capital fell from ~25% of assets (early 20th c.) to <10%
- Total international banking assets (Dec 2006): ~$29 trillion ≈ 63% of
  world GDP
- Ferguson's conclusion: poverty is seldom caused by rapacious bankers — it
  is more often caused by the **absence** of banks; credit and debt are
  essential building blocks of economic development

