## Chapter 2 (continued): Bonds and War — The Rothschilds and the Civil War

### The Rothschilds' Strategic Neutrality

- By mid-19th century the Rothschilds had evolved from bond traders into
  **fund managers** — now holding vast portfolios of government bonds
- Their interests shifted: wars that once generated business now threatened
  their holdings by raising default risk
- They were **hostile to national unification** in Italy and Germany for
  this reason — rising nationalism meant rising instability
- They had decided the Napoleonic Wars by backing Britain; they decided
  the American Civil War by **choosing to sit on the sidelines**

### *Driving Dixie Down* — The Confederate Finance Problem

- May 1863: **Ulysses S. Grant** captures Jackson, MS; forces
  **Lt.-Gen. John C. Pemberton** to Vicksburg; after siege, surrenders
  July 4 — Mississippi firmly under Union control
- But the real financial turning point came earlier: **April 29, 1862**,
  when **Flag Officer David Farragut** seized New Orleans
- Key thesis: the Confederacy lost as much from **lack of hard cash** as
  from lack of industrial capacity or manpower

### Confederate Finances — Structure and Failure

- At war's start, with no central tax system, the **Confederate Treasury**
  raised funds via two domestic bond issues: $15 million and $100 million
- But liquid capital was scarce in the agrarian South
- The Confederacy hoped the **Rothschilds** might finance them as they had
  helped Wellington beat Napoleon — the hope proved fanciful

### The Rothschild Agent and Anti-Semitic Accusations

- Rothschild New York agent **August Belmont** (Democratic Party national
  chairman) had backed **Stephen A. Douglas** against Lincoln in 1860;
  was a vocal critic of Lincoln's "fatal policy of confiscation and
  forcible emancipation"
- **Salomon de Rothschild**, James's son, had expressed pro-Southern
  sympathies before the war
- The *Chicago Tribune* (1864): *"Belmont, the Rothschilds, and the whole
  tribe of Jews . . . have been buying up Confederate bonds"*
- In reality the Rothschilds **opted not to back the South**: partly moral
  distaste for slavery; mainly because the Confederacy was a **bad credit
  risk** — Confederate president **Jefferson Davis** had openly advocated
  repudiation of state debts when a US senator

### The Erlanger Cotton Bond — An Ingenious Innovation

- Conventional Confederate bonds sold poorly in Europe
- Innovation: **cotton-backed bonds** issued by the French firm
  **Emile Erlanger and Co.**
- Terms: 7% coupon, 20-year maturity, convertible into cotton at
  the **pre-war price of 6d per pound**
- Why it worked briefly: cotton prices were *rising* due to wartime
  demand — bond price actually **doubled** Dec 1863–Sept 1864 despite
  Gettysburg and Vicksburg, because cotton prices kept rising
- The South also embargoed cotton exports to Liverpool to coerce Britain:
  cotton prices soared from 6¼d to 27¼d per pound; imports fell from
  2.6 million bales (1860) to under 72,000 (1862)
- The **"cotton famine"** threw half of Lancashire's 300,000 mill workers
  out of work; a quarter of the population was on poor relief
- Key buyers of Erlanger bonds: future PM **William Ewart Gladstone**
  and *The Times* editor **John Delane** — the embargo strategy was
  working politically

### Why the Cotton Bond Failed: The New Orleans Pivot

- The fatal flaw: **collateral is only as good as your ability to
  deliver it**
- When New Orleans fell (April 1862), any investor wanting to claim
  cotton had to run the Union naval blockade **twice** — in and out
- This made the cotton bond's collateral essentially inaccessible
- Rothschilds dismissed the Erlanger loan as *"of so speculative a
  nature that it was very likely to attract all wild speculators . . .
  we do not hear of any respectable people having anything to do with it"*
- By 1863 Lancashire mills had found new cotton sources in China, Egypt,
  and India — the leverage evaporated

### Confederate Monetary Collapse

- With domestic bonds exhausted and only two foreign loans raised, the
  Confederacy printed **$1.7 billion** in unbacked paper ("greybacks")
- Union "greenbacks" retained ~50 cents in gold value at war's end;
  Confederate greybacks were worth **one cent**
- Exacerbated by: state/municipal money printing; rampant forgery of
  crudely-made notes
- **Southern inflation: ~4,000%** during the Civil War vs. 60% in the
  North
- Investors in Confederate bonds lost everything — the victorious Union
  pledged not to honor Confederate debts
- Ferguson's conclusion: *"It would not be the last time in history that
  an attempt to buck the bond market would end in ruinous inflation and
  military humiliation"*

---

## Chapter 2 (continued): *The Euthanasia of the Rentier*

### Latin American Defaults and the Power of Bondholders

- The Confederacy was far from unique — debt defaults were near-universal
  in 19th-century Latin America
- **First great Latin American debt crisis: 1826–9**, when Peru, Colombia,
  Chile, Mexico, Guatemala, and Argentina all defaulted on London loans
- Key structural reason: the domestic bondholder class (with interest in
  sound currency) was weaker in Latin America than elsewhere
- Also: **"painless to default when a substantial proportion of
  bondholders are foreign"** — a pattern that would repeat throughout
  the 20th century

### Gunboat Diplomacy and Bondholder Enforcement

- Countries that defaulted risked economic sanctions, foreign control
  of finances, and — in at least **five cases** — military intervention
- **Gladstone ordered the invasion of Egypt in 1882** partly because
  the Egyptian government threatened to renege on obligations to European
  bondholders (including Gladstone himself)
- **Venezuela 1902**: joint naval expedition by Britain, Germany, and
  Italy temporarily blockaded Venezuelan ports after default
- The US was "especially energetic and effective" in protecting
  bondholders' interests in Central America and the Caribbean

### The Rentier Class and Its Structural Vulnerability

- British **rentiers** (bond interest recipients) in the early 19th
  century: fewer than 250,000 people — barely **2% of population**
- Yet their wealth exceeded the **entire national income of the UK**;
  their income ~7% of national income
- By 1822, interest on the national debt = roughly **half of total
  public spending**; more than two-thirds of tax revenue was indirect
  (i.e., fell on consumption by the many)
- **William Cobbett**, *Rural Rides* (1830):
> *"A national debt, and all the taxation and gambling belonging to
> it, have a natural tendency to draw wealth into great masses . . .
> for the gain of a few."*
- Radicals warned the country would end up in the hands of
  *"loan-jobbers, stock-jobbers . . . Jews and the whole tribe of
  tax-eaters"*
- Despite these critiques, the decades after 1830 were a **golden age
  for the rentier** — defaults became less frequent, the gold standard
  made money dependable
- The **rentiers** (Rothschilds, Barings, Gladstones) remained socially,
  politically, and economically intertwined — what ended their
  dominance was not democracy or socialism but the **First World War**

### The Five Steps to Wartime Inflation

**Milton Friedman**: *"Inflation is always and everywhere a monetary
phenomenon, in the sense that it cannot occur without a more rapid
increase in the quantity of money than in output."*

Ferguson's five-step mechanism for WWI-era inflation:
1. War → shortages of goods, **plus**
2. Short-term government borrowing from the central bank
3. Which turned debt into cash, **expanding the money supply**
4. Causing inflationary expectations to shift, demand for cash to fall
5. Prices of goods to rise

### Germany vs. Britain: Why Germany Got Hyperinflation

- Germany's banknote volume rose 1,040% (1913–1918); Britain 708%;
  France 386% — but Bulgaria rose 1,116%, Romania 961%
- Cost-of-living in Berlin 1918: 2.3× pre-war; London 2.1× — almost
  identical
- **Critical difference**: Germany could not access the international
  bond market during the war (having spurned, then been shut out of,
  the New York market)
- The **Entente powers** could sell bonds in the US and British Empire;
  the Central Powers were thrown back on domestic resources
- As domestic investor appetite was sated, Germany turned to central
  bank short-term borrowing → money supply expansion
- By war's end, roughly **a third of Reich debt was "floating"
  (unfunded)** — a monetary overhang suppressed only by wartime price
  controls

### The Versailles Trap and Weimar's Political Economy

- Defeat meant the enemy would *not* pay the war's costs — bills fell
  due in Berlin
- **Versailles Treaty (1921)**: Germany saddled with 132 billion
  "gold marks" in reparations — **more than 3× national income**
- Reparations accounted for more than a third of all Reich expenditure
  in 1921–22
- Ferguson's contrarian argument: the hyperinflation of 1923 was
  **not simply a consequence of Versailles**
- The **Weimar tax system was feeble** — new regime lacked legitimacy
  among higher-income groups who declined to pay; public money was
  spent recklessly on generous wage settlements for public sector unions
- Deficits in 1919–20 exceeded **10% of net national product** before
  reparations were even billed
- Weimar elites **calculated** that runaway currency depreciation would
  force the Allies to revise reparations — a miscalculation
- When France realized Germany's insincerity, they **invaded the Ruhr
  (1923)**; Germany financed a general strike ("passive resistance")
  with yet more printed money — the hyperinflationary endgame arrived

### The German Hyperinflation: Scale and Consequences

- By end of 1923: approximately **4.97 × 10²⁰ marks** in circulation
- Annual inflation rate peaked at **182 billion per cent**
- Prices averaged **1.26 trillion times** higher than in 1913

> *"Inflation is a crowd phenomenon in the strictest and most concrete
> sense of the word. '[It is] a witches' sabbath of devaluation where
> men and the units of their money have the strongest effects on each
> other . . . Together they are all at its mercy and all feel equally
> worthless.'"* — **Elias Canetti**, describing Frankfurt

- Hyperinflation wiped out **all internal debt** accumulated during and
  after the war — acting as a tax on fixed-income holders
- Principal victims: **rentiers**, senior civil servants, professionals
- Entrepreneurs could insulate themselves: adjust prices upward, hoard
  dollars, invest in "real assets," pay off debts in depreciating marks
- Economic legacy: weakened banks; chronically high interest rates with
  embedded inflation risk premium
- **Keynes (1923)** theorized the "euthanasia of the rentier" through
  inflation was preferable to mass unemployment through deflation

> *"By a continuing process of inflation, governments can confiscate,
> secretly and unobserved, an important part of the wealth of their
> citizens . . . all permanent relations between debtors and creditors,
> which form the ultimate foundation of capitalism, become so utterly
> disordered as to be almost meaningless."* — **Keynes** (1919)

- Keynes attributed the insight to Lenin: *"There is no subtler, no
  surer means of overturning the existing basis of society than to
  debauch the currency"*
- Bolshevik **Yevgeni Preobrazhensky** called the printing press
  *"that machine-gun of the Commissariat of Finance which poured fire
  into the rear of the bourgeois system"*
- Austria, Hungary, Poland, and Russia also suffered comparable
  currency collapses 1917–1924
- Ferguson's key distinction: *"Inflation is a monetary phenomenon . . .
  but hyperinflation is always and everywhere a **political** phenomenon"*

### Ferguson's Key Insight on Hyperinflation

- Inflation is monetary; **hyperinflation requires a fundamental
  malfunction of political economy**
- Germany's case: combination of internal gridlock + external defiance
  (refusal to accept defeat) → worst possible outcome
- There were less catastrophic ways to settle the conflicting claims of
  domestic and foreign creditors — Germany chose none of them

---

### Argentina: The Bond Market's Limits

### Bill Gross and the Bond as Gamble

- **Bill Gross** (PIMCO founder), a former Las Vegas blackjack player,
  sees bond-buying as gambling: the core bet is that inflation won't
  consume the fixed interest payments
- In the 1970s, with US inflation peaking at ~15% (April 1980),
  real annual returns on US government bonds were **minus 3%** — among
  the worst bond bear markets in history
- By 2007, only a handful of countries had inflation >10%; only
  Zimbabwe had hyperinflation — but in 1979 at least **seven countries**
  had annual inflation >50%, and **sixty+ countries** (including the US
  and UK) had double-digit inflation

### Argentina: From Richest to Basket Case

- In 1913 Argentina was among the **ten richest countries in the world**;
  outside the English-speaking world, per capita GDP exceeded only by
  Switzerland, Belgium, the Netherlands, and Denmark
- Between 1870–1913, Argentina's economy grew faster than both the US
  and Germany; almost as much foreign capital invested there as in Canada
- Symbol of wealth: **two Harrods stores** in the world — one in
  Knightsbridge, one in Buenos Aires
- **General Juan Domingo Perón** (elected Feb 1946), visiting the central
  bank: *"There is so much gold . . . you can hardly walk through the
  corridors"*

### Argentina's Decline: The Political Economy of Inflation

- Per capita GDP was the **same in 1988 as in 1959**; by 1998 had sunk
  to 34% of US level (vs. 72% in 1913)
- Had been overtaken by Singapore, Japan, Taiwan, South Korea — and
  most humiliatingly, **Chile**
- Inflation in double digits between 1945–52, 1956–68, 1970–74; treble
  or quadruple digits 1975–90; peaked at **5,000% per annum in 1989**
- Debt defaults: 1982, 1989, 2002, 2004

### Root Causes: Social Structure, Not Just Monetary Policy

- An **oligarchy of landowners** built the economy on agricultural
  exports; this failed comprehensively in the Depression
- Mass immigration without land redistribution → oversized, volatile
  urban working class susceptible to **populist mobilization**
- Military coup installed **José F. Uriburu** (1930); **Perón** offered
  something for everyone: better wages for workers, protective tariffs
  for industrialists
- Every subsequent government — military or civilian — failed to resolve
  the same conflict between agriculture and industry; each resorted to
  **currency devaluation and inflation**
- Perón's return (1973): annual inflation surged to **444%**
- Military junta (*Proceso de Reorganización Nacional*): 60% of GDP in
  external debt by 1984; economic devastation despite/alongside
  political terror
- Ferguson's core argument: no significant Argentine constituency had
  an interest in **price stability**
  - Owners of capital preferred deficits and devaluation
  - Labour was accustomed to wage-price spirals
  - The *descamisados* (the shirtless poor) had no savings to protect
  - The government benefited — its peso-denominated debts were
    inflated away

### The 1989 Hyperinflation Crisis

- February 1989: *monthly* inflation rate rising above 100%
- The mint **literally ran out of paper** and the printers went on strike
  — the Central Bank Vice-President: *"It's a physical problem . . .
  I don't know how we're going to do it, but the money has got to be
  there on Monday"*
- June: crowds in Rosario (Argentina's second city) rioted and looted;
  14 dead
- Principal losers: fixed-income earners — civil servants, academics,
  pensioners; principal beneficiaries: large debtors (including the
  government itself)

### External Debt and the Barings Precedent

- By 1983 external (dollar-denominated) debt: **$46 billion**;
  by 1989: $65 billion; eventually reached **$155 billion**
- Dollar debt could not be inflated away — only default could eliminate it
- **1890 Barings Crisis**: Baring Brothers brought to the brink of
  bankruptcy by Argentine bonds (including a failed Buenos Aires Water
  Supply and Drainage Company issue)
- The **Rothschilds** (Barings' rivals) persuaded the British government
  to contribute £1 million to a **£17 million bailout fund** — first Lord
  Rothschild chaired the reform committee; future loans conditioned on
  pegging the peso to gold via an independent currency board

### The Cavallo Plan and the 2001 Default

- **Domingo Cavallo** (Finance Minister) introduced the *peso
  convertible* in 1991 — Argentina's **sixth currency in a century**
- By 1996 inflation brought to zero; turned negative in 1999
- But: **monetary stricture without fiscal stricture** — public debt
  rose from 35% of GDP (1994) to 64% (2001) as governments borrowed
  from international bond markets rather than balancing budgets
- IMF bailouts: $15 billion (Jan 2001), $8 billion (May 2001);
  IMF declined a third lifeline
- **December 23, 2001**: Argentina announced a moratorium on its entire
  foreign debt — including **$81 billion in bonds** — the largest
  sovereign default in history at that time
- The spread between Argentine and US bonds was 664 basis points
  1998–2000 (significantly underpriced the actual risk); after default
  the spread hit **7,000+ basis points** by March 2002
- After protracted negotiations (152 varieties of paper, six currencies,
  eight jurisdictions) creditors accepted new bonds worth roughly
  **35 cents on the dollar** — one of history's most drastic "haircuts"

> Argentina's history: the bond market is **less powerful than it
> appears** — spreads consistently under-priced default risk, and even
> gunboat diplomacy couldn't permanently discipline a sovereign debtor
> when domestic politics made repayment impossible

<!-- pp. 101-120 -->

## Chapter 2 (conclusion): The Resurrection of the Rentier

### Why Bondholders Survived Keynes's Prediction
- **Keynes** had predicted the "euthanasia of the *rentier*" — inflation
  would eventually eat all paper wealth in government bonds
- Instead: **Great Inflation of the 1970s** gave way to one of the
  great bond bull markets of modern history
- Emerging market bond spreads fell to pre-WWI lows by early 2007 —
  implying near-unshakeable confidence in economic futures
- "Rumours of the death of Mr Bond have clearly proved to be exaggerated"

### Why Inflation Fell
- Cheaper goods from Asia (technology + low-wage labor relocation)
- **Monetarist-inspired** interest rate hikes by Bank of England and
  Federal Reserve in late 1970s/early 1980s
- Spread of **central bank independence** and explicit inflation targets
  in the 1990s
- Structural factors: weaker trade unions, privatization of loss-making
  state industries
- Most important: growing social constituency with an interest in
  positive real returns — pension funds and retirees

### Aging Societies and Bond Demand
- 2007 survey: bonds accounted for >25% of pension fund assets across
  11 major economies
- Italy (birthplace of the bond market): in 1965 only 10% of Italians
  were 65+; today ~20%; by 2050 projected to be nearly a third
- Aging societies structurally demand fixed income; recurrent deficits
  ensure bond supply never runs short
- Italy surrendered monetary sovereignty to the **European Central Bank**
  — no more option for Italian politicians to print money

### The Greenspan "Conundrum"
- Bush administration ran deficits in 7 of 8 years; federal debt grew
  from $5 trillion → $9+ trillion; CBO forecast $12+ trillion by 2017
- Paradox: bond market *rewarded* this profligacy — 10-year Treasury
  yield *declined* from 5.24% (Dec 2000) to 3.33% (Jun 2003)
- **Alan Greenspan** called this failure of yields to respond to
  short-term rate rises a "conundrum"
- Ferguson's pivot: to understand this, must look beyond sovereign debt
  to the stock market — "its younger and in many ways more dynamic sibling"

---

## Chapter 3: Blowing Bubbles

### The Joint-Stock Company — Why It Matters
- Next evolutionary step after banking and bond markets: the
  **joint-stock, limited-liability corporation**
- **Joint-stock**: capital jointly owned by multiple investors
- **Limited-liability**: company's separate legal existence protects
  investors — loss capped at their investment if venture fails
- Enables thousands of individuals to pool resources for risky,
  long-term projects requiring vast capital before profits materialize
- Small enterprises could operate as partnerships; those aspiring to
  span continents *needed* the company

### How Stock Markets Work
- Stock markets discipline companies where vigilant shareholders cannot
- Share price = collective estimate of a company's future earnings
- "Stock markets hold hourly referendums on companies"
- But markets have a life of their own: future is uncertain, humans are
  prone to myopia and mood swings

### Irrational Exuberance and Animal Spirits
- When prices surge in sync: **collective euphoria** — **Alan Greenspan**'s
  "**irrational exuberance**"
- When "animal spirits" flip from greed to fear, bubbles burst with
  amazing suddenness
- Zoological imagery endemic to markets: bulls, bears, "electronic herd"
- Stock markets are mirrors of the *human* psyche — can become depressed,
  even suffer complete breakdowns; yet hope (or amnesia) always triumphs

### The Five Stages of a Bubble
Ferguson distills 400 years of bubble history into five stages
(following economist **Hyman Minsky**):

1. **Displacement** — some change in economic circumstances creates new
   profitable opportunities
2. **Euphoria** (overtrading) — feedback process: rising expected profits
   lead to rapid share price growth
3. **Mania** (bubble) — prospect of easy capital gains attracts
   first-time investors and swindlers
4. **Distress** — insiders realize expected profits cannot justify
   exorbitant prices; begin selling
5. **Revulsion** (discredit) — outsiders stampede for exits; bubble bursts

### Three Structural Features of Every Bubble
- **Asymmetric information**: insiders know far more than outsiders;
  in a bubble, they exploit this *fraudulently*
- **Cross-border capital flows**: bubbles more likely when capital flows
  freely; seasoned speculators better at timing exits than naive
  first-timers — not everyone is equally irrational
- **Easy credit**: "without easy credit creation a true bubble cannot
  occur" — bubbles typically trace back to central bank sins of
  omission or commission

### Business Week as Contrary Indicator
- **13 August 1979**: *Business Week* cover — "The Death of Equities:
  How inflation is destroying the stock market." Dow at 875, nearly
  17% below its 1973 peak of 1052
- What happened next: Dow bottomed at 777 in Aug 1982, then *tripled*
  to 2,700 by summer 1987, then continued rising to 10,395 by
  27 September 1999 — nearly **12-fold** in 20 years

> "Conditions don't have to get a lot better to justify Dow 36,000"
> — James K. Glassman & Kevin A. Hassett, *Dow 36,000* (1999),
> arguing P/E of 100x was "perfectly reasonable"

- That article appeared less than four months before the dot-com crash;
  by Oct 2002 Dow was at 7,286; still trading at one-third of Glassman/
  Hassett's target at time of writing (April 2008)

### Long-Run Stock Returns: The Data
- $10,000 invested in US stocks in 1964 with dividends reinvested →
  **$700,000** by 2007 (factor of ~70)
- US bonds: factor of ~23; US bills: factor of ~12
- Adjusted for inflation (~7x cost of living rise): stocks up **10.3x**
  real; bonds 3.4x; bills 1.8x; cash held as dollar bills: **down 85%**
- Best global market long-run: **US stocks** at 4.73% real per year
  (1920s–1990s); Sweden 3.71%; Switzerland 3.03%; UK 2.28%
- 10 out of 27 markets studied had **negative long-term real returns**
  — worst: Venezuela, Peru, Colombia, Argentina (−5.36%)
- "Stocks for the long run" is not a universally applicable nostrum

### Why Stocks Beat Bonds Over Time
- Bonds = promises by governments to pay interest + repay principal;
  many fail via default or currency depreciation
- Stocks = share of a *profit-making corporation*; successful companies
  pay dividends AND appreciate
- Risk is real: stocks more volatile, companies more likely to go bankrupt
  than sovereign states; in bankruptcy, bond holders paid first,
  equity holders may get nothing
- Superior returns = **equity risk premium** — a risk often worth taking

---

### The Company You Keep: John Law and the Origins of the Stock Bubble

### John Law — The Man Who Invented the Stock Market Bubble
- Memorial inscription in Venice's San Moise church: "To the honour and
  memory of **John Law** of Edinburgh. Most distinguished controller of
  the treasury of the kings of the French."
- A convicted murderer, compulsive gambler, flawed financial genius —
  responsible for the first true boom-and-bust in asset prices
- May also have caused the French Revolution by destroying the *ancien
  régime*'s best chance to reform its finances
- Born Edinburgh 1671; son of a goldsmith; heir to Lauriston Castle
- Fled to Amsterdam in 1694 after killing a man in a duel and escaping
  from prison

### Amsterdam 1690s — World Capital of Financial Innovation
- Dutch had built the world's first central bank: the **Amsterdam Exchange
  Bank** (*Wisselbank*, 1609) — solved debased coinage problem
- Single greatest Dutch invention: the **joint-stock company**

### Origins of the VOC
- Dutch merchants sought to wrest the Asian spice trade from Portugal/Spain
- Spices (cinnamon, cloves, mace, nutmeg, pepper) preserved and flavored
  food; for centuries came overland via the Spice Road
- Portuguese discovery of sea route to East Indies via Cape of Good Hope
  opened vast new opportunities
- Round trips: avg well over 14 months; 1598 voyage — 22 ships out,
  only 12 returned safely → merchants pooled resources
- By 1600: ~6 fledgling East India companies out of Dutch ports, each
  with a fixed term (usually one voyage), capital repaid at end
- Fixed-term model couldn't build the permanent bases/fortifications
  needed to displace Portugal and Spain
- **Dutch States-General** (parliament) merged existing companies into
  a single entity: the **VOC** (*Vereenigde Nederlandsche Geoctroyeerde
  Oostindische Compagnie* — United Dutch Chartered East India Company),
  formally chartered **1602**
- Monopoly on all Dutch trade east of Cape of Good Hope and west of
  Straits of Magellan

### VOC Structure and the First IPO
- Subscription open to all residents of the United Provinces; no upper
  limit on capital raised
- Amsterdam alone: 1,143 subscribers; 445 invested less than 1,000
  guilders; only 80 invested more than 10,000
- Total raised: **6.45 million guilders** — dwarfed rival English East
  India Company (£68,373 / ~820,000 guilders, just 219 subscribers)
- Capital divided among six regional chambers (Amsterdam, Zeeland,
  Enkhuizen, Delft, Hoorn, Rotterdam)
- 70 directors (*bewindhebbers*) formed the **Heeren XVII** (Seventeen
  Lords) — company board; Amsterdam had 57.4% of capital but only 8
  of 17 board seats
- Shares called *partijen* or *actien* ("a piece of the action");
  paid in installments 1603–1607
- Certificates were receipts, not formal share certificates; ownership
  recorded in VOC stock ledger
- **Limited liability** implied but not explicit: shareholders lost only
  their investment; Article 17 promised dividends only after profits
  reached 5% of initial capital

### Birth of the Stock Market
- VOC did not publish accounts in 1612 as required; directors petitioned
  out of the obligation; capital repayment indefinitely postponed
- 1612: VOC declared it would not liquidate → shareholders wanting cash
  *had to sell to another investor* — the secondary market was born
- By 1607, fully **one-third** of VOC stock had been transferred from
  original owners — remarkably liquid from the start
- Forward market in VOC shares emerged (sales for future delivery) —
  informal open-air markets on the **Warmoesstraat** or near the Oude Kerk
- 1608: covered **Beurs** (stock exchange) built on the Rokin; looked
  like a medieval Oxford college

> "Hand-shakes are followed by shouting, insults, impudence, pushing
> and shoving." — contemporary description of Amsterdam Beurs trading floor

- Bulls (*liefhebbers*) did battle with bears (*contremines*)
- **1609**: Amsterdam Exchange Bank founded — stock market needed a
  functioning monetary system; banks accepted VOC shares as collateral
- Company + bourse + bank = "triangular foundation for a new kind of economy"

### VOC Governance Battles (Proto-Shareholder Activism)
- Disgruntled ex-director **Isaac le Maire** organized a short-selling
  attack on VOC shares to pressure management; ruined by 1611 dividend
- 1622 pamphlet *The Necessary Discourse* (*Nootwendich Discours*):
  criticized "self-serving governance" and opaque accounts

> "The account book, we can only surmise, must have been rubbed with
> bacon and fed to the dogs." — anonymous dissident shareholder, 1622

- Charter renewed 1622 with reforms: directors limited to 3-year terms;
  "Nine Men" elected by large shareholders to oversee accounts
- 1632: standard **12.5% dividend** set (twice the borrowing rate);
  virtually all net profits distributed; shareholders protected from dilution
- Capital base remained essentially unchanged throughout VOC's existence;
  additional capital raised via **bonds**, not new shares

### VOC's Commercial Empire
- **Jan Pieterszoon Coen**: made VOC profitable in mid-17th century;
  bellicose governor-general who understood "We cannot make war without
  trade, nor trade without war"
- Seized Jakarta (renamed **Batavia**) 1619; wiped out indigenous
  Bandanese; executed British East India Company officials at Amboyna
- By 1650s: effective monopoly on cloves, mace, nutmeg; also hub for
  intra-Asian trade (Japanese silver → Indian textiles → Chinese gold/silk)
- Principal-agent problem: employees traded on own account and defrauded
  the company; partially countered by compensation tied to turnover,
  not net profits
- 1620s: 50 VOC ships returned from Asia annually; by 1690s: 156
- By 1760: VOC shipping still ~3x British shipping volume

### VOC Share Price — A Century of Appreciation, No Bubble
- 1602–1733: VOC stock rose from par (100) to all-time peak of **786**
- By 1650: total dividends already 8x original investment — implied
  annual return of **27%**
- Key contrast: unlike the Dutch tulip bubble (1636-7), VOC's ascent
  was *gradual* over 100+ years; descent took 60+ years to fall back
  to 120 (December 1794)
- Rise and fall tracked the rise and fall of the Dutch Empire
- No VOC *bubble* — other monopoly trading companies would behave
  very differently (soaring and crashing in months)

### John Law Absorbs Amsterdam's Lessons
- Law was fascinated by the VOC/Exchange Bank/Beurs triangle
- Marvelled at short-sellers spreading negative rumors; specialists in
  *windhandel* (trading shares they didn't own)
- Concluded Dutch system was incomplete: wrong to restrict share issuance
  when demand was insatiable; Exchange Bank too conservative
- **Key insight**: bank money was just ledger entries; Law wanted paper
  notes that could *supplant* coins as currency
- 1705: submitted proposal to Scottish parliament for a new bank
  (*Money and Trade Considered*); rejected before Act of Union with England
- 1711: pitched **Victor Amadeus II, Duke of Savoy** on paper currency

> "I have discovered the secret of the philosopher's stone, it is to
> make gold out of paper." — John Law to a friend

- Duke demurred: "I am not rich enough to ruin myself."
- Law's next target: France (to be covered in subsequent pages)

<!-- pp. 121-140 -->

## Chapter 3 (cont.): The Mississippi Bubble — John Law's System

### Why France? The Fiscal Crisis Context

- France chosen because its fiscal problems were uniquely desperate —
  the wars of **Louis XIV** left the crown on brink of its third
  bankruptcy in under a century
- A *Visa* (debt review) had cancelled and reduced many debts (partial
  default); still needed 250 million new *billets d'état*
  (interest-bearing notes) to fund the current deficit
- Attempt to reduce gold/silver coinage backfired, plunging the
  economy into recession — Law claimed to have the solution

### Building the System: Banque Générale to Banque Royale

- October 1715: Law's first proposal (a public note-issuing bank) was
  rejected; a private bank succeeded
- **Banque Générale** established May 1716 under Law — licensed to
  issue notes payable in specie for 20 years; capital 6 million
  livres (effective ~2.85 million after depreciated billets d'état
  counted as 3/4 of paid capital)
- 1717: Banque Générale notes decreed legal tender for all tax payments
- Law's vision: Dutch model but with a crucial difference — paper money
  backed by absolutist state power rather than parliamentary constraint
- His theory: "an absolute prince who knows how to govern can extend
  his credit further and find needed funds at a lower interest rate
  than a prince who is limited in his authority" — **absolutist theory
  of finance**
- December 1718: Banque Générale became the **Banque Royale** — first
  French central bank; notes exchangeable for *écus de banque* or
  *livres tournois*

### The Mississippi Company Expansion

- 1717: **Compagnie d'Occident** (Company of the West) granted 25-year
  monopoly over Louisiana commerce; capital 100 million livres;
  shares 500 livres each, purchasable with the depreciated
  *billets d'état* — effectively monetizing government debt as equity
- **Duke of Saint-Simon** warned presciently: such a bank works only
  in republics or England where financiers control it; in an absolute
  monarchy the king can overthrow the bank at will

> "An establishment of this sort may be good in itself; but it is only
> so in a republic or a monarchy like England, whose finances are
> controlled by those alone who furnish them... But in a state which
> is weak, changeable, and absolute, like France, stability must
> necessarily be wanting to it." — Duke of Saint-Simon

- May 1719: Company absorbed East India and China companies → became
  **Compagnie des Indes** (Mississippi Company)
- July–September 1719: Law acquired royal mint profits (9-year lease),
  indirect tax farm lease, and agreed to lend 1.2 billion livres to
  the crown to pay off the entire royal debt
- October 1719: Law took control of direct tax collection
- Result: Law simultaneously ran what would be the equivalent of all
  top 500 US corporations, the US Treasury, and the Federal Reserve

### The Bubble Mechanics

- Share issuances deliberately structured to fuel price inflation:
  - "Mothers" (original 500-livre shares) → "daughters" (550 livres,
    June 1719) → "granddaughters" (1,000 livres, July 1719)
  - Each tranche diluted prior shareholders — logically should have
    lowered per-share price; instead price soared
- **Banque Royale** allowed shareholders to borrow against shares as
  collateral to buy more shares — self-reinforcing leverage loop
- Price trajectory: 2,750 livres (1 Aug) → 4,100 (30 Aug) → 5,000
  (4 Sep) → 9,000 (autumn) → **10,025 (2 December 1719)**
- Informal futures market: 12,500 livres for March 1720 delivery

> "Have you all gone crazy in Paris? It is a chaos I cannot fathom..."
> — **Voltaire** to M. de Génonville, 1719

- **Richard Cantillon** (Irish banker/economist) so certain of
  implosion he sold up and left Paris in August 1719 — made a fortune
- **Daniel Defoe** dismissed it from London: the French had merely
  "run up a piece of refined air"
- The word ***millionaire*** was coined during this frenzy — both
  millionaires and entrepreneurs were French inventions
- **rue Quincampoix**: the Company's share-issuing street became
  thronged by "princes and princesses, dukes and peers" who "sell
  estates and pawn jewels to purchase Mississippi"
- December 1719: Law converted to Catholicism; appointed
  **Controller General of Finances** — at peak he personally
  controlled all French indirect taxes, the entire national debt,
  26 royal mints, Louisiana colony, the Mississippi Company, the
  fur trade, and all of France's trade with Africa, Asia, East Indies

> Louis XIV said 'L'état, c'est moi.' John Law could say:
> 'L'économie, c'est moi.'

### Law's Personal Speculation and Conflict of Interest

- The structural problem: as majority shareholder in the company AND
  controller of the central bank, Law had every incentive to inflate
  the bubble rather than prick it
- He actually short-sold £100,000 of **East India Company** stock
  (for £180,000) betting British shares would fall — a bet that
  cost him dearly when London prices rose to £420 by June 1720

### The Collapse: Five Stages of the Bubble Cycle

- **Phase 4 — Distress**: Mississippi share price began declining
  December 1719; Law opened a bureau at Banque Royale guaranteeing
  to buy/sell shares at a floor of 9,000 livres
- February 1720: Company absorbed Banque Royale; Law created
  *primes* (options) at 1,000 livres to buy a share at 10,000
  over 6 months (above the actual 10,100 peak — options were
  immediately worthless)
- **Inflation crisis**: by May 1720 total money supply (notes +
  shares redeemable at will) was roughly **4× larger** in livre
  terms than all the gold and silver France had previously used
- Paris prices in September 1720 were double what they'd been two
  years before — nearly all the increase in the previous 11 months
- Law's authoritarian response: banknotes made **legal tender**;
  gold/silver export banned; production and sale of gold objects
  banned; by arrêt of 27 February 1720, **illegal to possess more
  than 500 livres of metal coin** — houses could be searched

> Voltaire called the coin prohibition "the most unjust edict ever
> rendered" and "the final limit of a tyrannical absurdity."

- Law altered official gold price 28 times and silver price 35 times
  between September 1719 and December 1720 — chaotic, contradictory
  regulations bewildered the public

### The Final Crash

- 21 May 1720: Desperate decree to cut share price from 9,000 to 5,000
  livres in monthly steps AND halve banknotes in circulation —
  revoked 6 days later after violent public outcry, but confidence
  was permanently broken
- Share price: 9,005 (16 May) → 4,200 (31 May)
- Crowds outside the Bank; windows broken; "The heaviest loss falls
  on the people of this country and affects all ranks and conditions"
- Law dismissed 29 May, placed under house arrest; Banque Royale
  closed its doors
- Brief comeback as **Intendant General of Commerce** — shares
  rallied to 6,350 on 6 June; by October gold/silver reintroduced
  for domestic transactions; share price hit 2,000 in September and
  1,000 in December
- Law fled France in December 1720 with almost nothing

> "I acknowledge that I have made great mistakes. I made them because
> I am only human, and all men are liable to err. But I declare that
> none of these acts proceeded from malice or dishonesty."
> — John Law to the Duke of Orleans on departing

### Long-Term Consequences for France

- Mississippi Bubble **fatally set back France's financial
  development** — put Frenchmen off paper money and stock markets
  for generations
- French monarchy's fiscal crisis went unresolved; crown lurched from
  one abortive reform to another through Louis XV and Louis XVI until
  royal bankruptcy precipitated the **French Revolution**
- Dutch satire collected in *The Great Scene of Folly* (1720):
  demented investors, barearsed brokers eating coin, Law in a carriage
  with "castles in the air"
- **Bernard Picart**, *Monument Consecrated to Posterity* (1721):
  allegorical engraving — naked Fortuna raining Mississippi stock on
  a mob, a juggernaut crushing an accountant

### Mississippi vs. South Sea: A Tale of Two Bubbles

- Contemporary **South Sea Bubble** in Britain was significantly
  smaller and ruined fewer people — key structural difference:
  **South Sea Company never gained control of the Bank of England**
  as Law had controlled Banque Royale
- **John Blunt**'s South Sea scheme: convert war debt (War of Spanish
  Succession) into equity of a company with monopoly on South
  American trade — same debt-to-equity conversion logic
- South Sea shares: £300 in April 1720 → £1,000 in June; instalments,
  loans against shares, generous dividends — same mania mechanics
- But Blunt faced the Bank of England as a competitor, the Whigs in
  Parliament as opponents, and had to pay massive bribes
  (Secretary to the Treasury alone: £249,000 from share options)
- **Bubble Act** passed 1720 to restrict new company flotations
  (190 companies had rushed to raise capital)
- South Sea Company's bank (**Sword Blade Company**) failed
  24 September — unlike Banque Royale, its notes were not legal tender
- Price rise ratio: South Sea 9.5× peak-to-par vs. Mississippi 19.6×
- No lasting systemic damage in England; South Sea Company continued
  to exist; government debt conversion not reversed

---

## Section: *Bulls and Bears* — The 1929 Crash

### Irving Fisher's Fatal Declaration

- 16 October 1929: **Irving Fisher** (Yale economist) declared US
  stock prices had "reached what looks like a permanently high plateau"
- 8 days later: **Black Thursday** — DJIA fell 2%; already declining
  since early September
- **Black Monday** (28 Oct): -13%; next day: -12%
- Over 3 years the US market declined **89%**, reaching nadir in
  July 1932; didn't regain 1929 peak until **November 1954**
- Output collapsed by a third; unemployment hit a quarter of the
  civilian labour force (a third by modern definition)
- World trade shrank by **two thirds**; international financial
  system fell apart in debt defaults, capital controls, and currency
  depreciations; only Soviet Union (autarkic) unaffected

### Structural Roots of the Depression

- Global over-capacity from WWI: non-European agricultural and
  industrial production had expanded during the war; when European
  production resumed, chronic over-supply drove down commodity prices
  long before 1929
- Countries with large war debts (esp. **Germany** with reparations)
  couldn't earn enough hard currency to service external creditors
- War had strengthened organized labour — employers couldn't cut wages
  as prices fell; profit margins squeezed → layoffs → demand collapse
- Yet the US itself was in fine economic shape before the crash:
  **RCA** (radio) rose 939% between 1925–1929; P/E ratio at peak: 73
  New innovations: **DuPont** (nylon), **Procter & Gamble** (soap),
  **Revlon**, **RCA**, **IBM** — genuine productivity revolution
- **Alfred Sloan** at GM revolutionizing management practices
- The genuine displacement (tech + consumer durables on instalment
  credit) provided the initial fuel for a classic bubble

### The Bubble Mechanics of 1929

- Investment trusts proliferated — new financial institutions designed
  to capitalize on the boom (**Goldman Sachs** Trading Corporation
  announced 8 August 1929)
- Leverage: small investors bought stocks on margin (brokers' loans
  often supplied by corporations, not banks)
- Insiders like **Charles E. Mitchell** (National City Bank) and
  **William Crapo Durant** (GM); ingenuous outsiders like
  **Groucho Marx**

### Friedman-Schwartz Thesis

- **Milton Friedman** and **Anna Schwartz** (*A Monetary History of
  the United States*): the **Federal Reserve System** bore primary
  responsibility for turning the 1929 crisis into the Great Depression
- They did NOT blame the Fed for the bubble — under **Benjamin Strong**
  (Federal Reserve Bank of New York) a reasonable balance had been
  struck between domestic and international considerations
- Argument: after Strong's death, Fed's subsequent monetary
  contraction transformed a crash into catastrophe

<!-- pp. 141-160 -->

## Chapter 3 (continued): Blowing Bubbles

### The Fed's Five Failures (1930–1933)

- After **Benjamin Strong**'s death from tuberculosis (October 1928),
  the Federal Reserve Board in Washington took over from the NY Fed —
  with catastrophic results
- **Five critical failures** of Fed policy deepened the Depression:
  1. **Credit contraction not countered** — Nov–Dec 1930: 608 banks
     failed with $550M in deposits, including the **Bank of United
     States** (alone >1/3 of total deposits lost); merger talks that
     might have saved it collapsed
  2. **Fed reduced credit outstanding** (Dec 1930–Apr 1931) — forced
     banks into frantic asset sales, crashing bond prices; Feb–Aug 1931
     wave: deposits fell $2.7B (9% of total)
  3. **Britain left gold standard** (Sept 1931) → foreign banks rushed
     to convert dollars to gold → Fed raised discount rate to 3.5%;
     halted external drain but destroyed 1,860 more US banks (Aug
     1931–Jan 1932, deposits: $1.45B); Fed gold reserves still exceeded
     legal requirements by >$1B — gold was NOT the binding constraint
  4. **Large-scale open market operations only begun April 1932** under
     massive political pressure — first real step, but too late to
     avert final wave of failures in Q4 1932 and first statewide
     'bank holidays'
  5. **Raised rates again** when Roosevelt devaluation rumors sparked
     dollar-to-gold flight — set scene for nationwide bank holiday
     (6 March 1933), from which **2,000 banks never returned**

- **Scale of the 'great contraction'**: 1929–1933
  - Public cash holdings +31%
  - Commercial bank deposits -37%
  - Bank loans -47%
  - Net: $1.2B increase in cash achieved at cost of $15.6B drop in
    deposits and $19.6B drop in loans — equivalent to **19% of 1929 GDP**
  - ~10,000 bank failures total

> "Inept or inflexible monetary policy in the wake of a sharp decline
> in asset prices can turn a correction into a recession and a recession
> into a depression." — Ferguson summarizing Friedman & Schwartz

- **Friedman & Schwartz** lesson: Fed should have aggressively injected
  liquidity via open market operations from 1929 onward, paid less
  attention to gold outflows
- Later view: the **inter-war gold standard itself** was the problem —
  it transmitted crises (like 1931 European bank/currency crises)
  internationally; stable exchange rates benefit not worth the cost
  of domestic deflation
- Ferguson's pointed footnote: "Anyone who doubts lessons can be
  learned from history needs only compare the writings and recent
  actions of the current chairman of the Federal Reserve System"
  (i.e., **Ben Bernanke**, who wrote his PhD on the Depression)

---

### A Tale of Fat Tails

- **Hyman Minsky** observation: "The most significant economic event
  of the era since World War II is something that has not happened:
  there has not been a deep and long-lasting depression"
- **Fat tails problem**: stock market returns do NOT follow a normal
  (bell-curve) distribution like human heights
  - Under normal distribution, a 10%+ annual drop would occur once
    every 500 years — on the Dow it has happened ~once every 5 years
  - 20%+ crashes would be virtually impossible statistically; in fact
    **nine such crashes** occurred in the past century

### Black Monday, 1987

- **19 October 1987**: Dow fell 23% in a single session — one of only
  four single-day drops >10% in index history
- Peak-to-trough loss: ~one-third of value of American stocks,
  ~$1 trillion
- Causes: Fed had raised rates from 5.5% to 6% the prior month; but
  **Nicholas Brady** task force blamed 'mechanical, price-insensitive
  selling' via **portfolio insurance** strategies, plus lack of
  **circuit breakers** on futures/options markets
- **What didn't happen**: no Great Depression, no recession in 1988
  (only mild 1990–91 recession); Dow recovered to pre-crash levels
  within a year

- Key credit: **Alan Greenspan**, just 2 months into his Fed chairmanship
  - 20 October statement: Fed affirmed 'readiness to serve as a source
    of liquidity to support the economic and financial system'
  - Aggressively bought government bonds; cut Fed borrowing costs
    nearly 2% in sixteen days
  - Minsky's 'It' (a second Great Depression) had not happened

### The Greenspan Era and the Dot-Com Bubble

- After 1987, Greenspan's dilemma: act pre-emptively to prevent the
  next panic, or wait?
- **1990s tech bubble**: displacement = personal computers + Internet;
  accommodative monetary policy also fuelled it
  - Fed funds rate cut from 6% (June 1995) to 5.25% (Jan 1996–Feb
    1997); raised to 5.5% in March 1997; then cut in steps Sep–Nov
    1998 to 4.75%; held at 4.75% until May 1999 (Dow crossed 10,000)
- Why did Greenspan let euphoria run? Four reasons:
  1. Underestimated tech bubble momentum (FOMC speculated market near
     peak as early as Dec 1995 with Dow at 5,000)
  2. Believed it was not the Fed's role to worry about **asset price
     inflation**, only consumer price inflation
  3. Thought tech boom was genuinely improving productivity, lowering
     CPI inflation
  4. **Russian debt default** (Aug 1998) forced rate cuts for external
     reasons; also inherited doctrine from **William McChesney Martin**
     ("remove the punchbowl") but Greenspan no longer believed it

- Greenspan's 'just-in-time' monetary policy avoided 1930s repeat AND
  Japan-style outcome (1990 BoJ rate hike → 80% stock selloff + decade
  of stagnation) — but at a cost: the **asset bubble created conditions
  for malfeasance**

> The nineties resembled "a re-run of the Roaring Twenties" in stock
> trajectory — but in other ways more like a rerun of the 1720s.

### Enron: The Mississippi Company of the 1990s

- **Enron** = the company that would be to the dot-com bubble what
  **John Law**'s Mississippi Company was to the South Sea Bubble
  - Named *Fortune*'s "America's Most Innovative Company" for six
    consecutive years (1996–2001)
- **Kenneth Lay** parallels to John Law:
  - Both from humble origins; both positioned company as reinventing
    finance/energy; both had government friends enabling the scheme
  - Lay's McKinsey-supplied idea (**Jeffrey K. Skilling**): create an
    'Energy Bank' acting as intermediary between suppliers and
    consumers — rather than utilities physically owning pipelines
  - **George H.W. Bush** deregulated energy in 1992; ~75% of Enron's
    $6.6M in political contributions went to Republicans; **Phil Gramm**
    (Enron's 2nd-largest campaign recipient) championed Californian
    energy deregulation
- By end of 2000: America's 4th-largest company, ~21,000 employees,
  controlled 1/4 of US natural gas business; had assets across Latin
  America, pipeline in Argentina (via George W. Bush's intervention)
- Stock rose ~5x from <$20 to >$90 in three years after 1997
- Top 140 executives paid avg $5.3M each in final year;
  **Skilling**: "All that matters is money... You buy loyalty with money"

### Enron's Fraud Mechanics

- The 'System' was elaborate fraud: **mark-to-market accounting** and
  **debt securitization** used to disguise losses
- Losses concealed in **special-purpose entities (SPEs)** — not
  consolidated in company statements
  - CFO **Andrew Fastow** created SPEs with names like Raptor I, Talon,
    Chewco Investments; he and others secretly unloaded $924M of
    Enron shares while the going was good
- **EnronOnline** (first web-based commodity-trading system) had high
  turnover but unclear profitability
- California: after deregulation, traders were heard on tape asking
  **El Paso Electric** to shut down production to maintain prices;
  California experienced **38 rolling blackouts** in just 6 months
- **Sherron Watkins** wrote to Lay in August 2001 warning Enron would
  'implode in a wave of accounting scandals'
- Collapse timeline:
  - Oct 16, 2001: $618M Q3 loss + $1.2B shareholder equity reduction
  - Oct 24: Fastow resigned as CFO (SEC inquiry pending)
  - Nov 8: profits for preceding 5 years restated; overstatement: $567M
  - Dec 2, 2001: bankruptcy filed — long-term debt understated by $25B
    (actual $38B vs. stated $13B)
  - End of 2001: Enron shares worth just 30 cents
- **Alan Greenspan** had accepted the Enron Prize for Distinguished
  Public Service in November 2001 — two weeks before the bankruptcy

> "John Law's philosopher's stone had allowed him 'to make gold out
> of paper'. Ken Lay's equivalent was 'to make gold out of gas'."

- Verdicts: Lay found guilty on all 10 charges (died before sentencing
  in Aspen); Skilling guilty on 18/27 counts, sentenced to 24 years
  + repay $26M; auditors **Arthur Andersen** destroyed
- Losers: ordinary employees and small shareholders whose savings
  became 'wind' — like the millions of livres lost in the Mississippi crash

### Conclusion of Chapter 3

- **Central thesis**: joint-stock, limited-liability companies are
  genuinely miraculous — but crooked companies and irrational markets
  go hand in hand; **central bankers** are the cowboys who are supposed
  to control the herd
- Without loose Fed money in the 1990s, Lay and Skilling couldn't have
  run Enron's stock to $90; without Banque Royale, Law couldn't have
  run the Mississippi scheme
- The **Dutch East India Company** model (with sound money from the
  Amsterdam Exchange Bank) shows bubbles and busts CAN be avoided
- Market path will always be jagged because human expectations swing
  from over-optimism to over-pessimism; the investor's hope: crashes
  come on "a smooth ski-slope and not over a sheer cliff"

---

## Chapter 4: Taking Cover (Insurance)

### Origins of Insurance

- **Bottomry** — insuring merchant ships' hulls — was the earliest form;
  some contracts date to 14th-century Italy, appearing in business docs as *securitas*
- Earliest arrangements were essentially conditional loans (cancellable on mishap),
  not true policies in the modern sense; in *The Merchant of Venice*,
  Antonio's "argosies" are conspicuously uninsured
- True insurance contracts appear by the 1350s; premiums 15–20% of sum insured,
  falling below 10% by the 15th century
- **Francesco Datini** (c. 1335–1410) contract covers risks "of God, of the sea,
  of men of war, of fire, of jettison, of detainment by princes" — comprehensive template
- Contracts eventually standardized into the *lex mercatoria* (mercantile law)

### Lloyd's and the London Market

- **Great Fire of 1666** (13,000+ houses destroyed) focused minds on fire risk
- **Nicholas Barbon** established the first fire insurance company fourteen years later
- Marine insurance coalesced at **Edward Lloyd's coffee house** in Tower Street;
  by 1774 the **Society of Lloyd's** was formalized at the Royal Exchange —
  initially 79 members, each paying a £15 subscription
- Lloyd's underwriters had **unlimited liability** (they literally wrote names under contracts —
  hence "Lloyd's Names"); operated on pay-as-you-go, not reserve accumulation
- **Sun Insurance Office (1710)** brought limited liability to insurance;
  **Royal Exchange Assurance** and **London Assurance Corporation** followed in 1720
- On the eve of WWI, most of Germany's merchant marine was insured by Lloyd's

### The Mathematical Foundations of Insurance

> All early insurance — even sophisticated shipping cover — was essentially a form of gambling.
> There did not yet exist an adequate theoretical basis for evaluating risks.

Six intellectual breakthroughs, beginning ~1660, created that basis:

1. **Probability** — **Blaise Pascal** (*Ars Cogitandi*): fear of harm should be proportional
   not just to gravity of harm but to *probability* of the event; developed with
   **Pierre de Fermat**
2. **Life expectancy** — **John Graunt** (1662) *Natural and Political Observations on
   the Bills of Mortality* — first systematic mortality statistics; limited by lack of
   age-at-death data. **Edmund Halley** solved this using Breslau data:
   1,238 births and 1,174 deaths; his life table gave "100 to 1 that a Man of 20
   dies not in a year, and but 38 to 1 for a Man of 50" — founding stone of
   **actuarial mathematics**
3. **Certainty / Law of Large Numbers** — **Jacob Bernoulli** (1705): under similar
   conditions, past patterns predict future occurrence; basis of statistical significance
   and confidence intervals
4. **Normal distribution** — **Abraham de Moivre** (1733): outcomes of iterated
   processes cluster around the mean; 68.2% within one standard deviation — the bell curve
5. **Utility** — **Daniel Bernoulli** (1738): value must be based on utility, not price;
   marginal utility of wealth declines — $100 is worth more to a median earner than
   a hedge fund manager
6. **Inference** — **Thomas Bayes** (*Essay Towards Solving a Problem in the Doctrine of
   Chances*, 1764, posthumous): expected utility = probability of event × payoff;
   foundation of Bayesian probability

> "It was not merchants but mathematicians who were the true progenitors of modern insurance.
> Yet it took clergymen to turn theory into practice."

### The Scottish Ministers' Widows' Fund (1744)

- **Robert Wallace** (minister, Greyfriars) and **Alexander Webster** (minister, Tolbooth),
  with mathematician **Colin Maclaurin** (Professor of Mathematics, Edinburgh),
  created the first modern insurance fund based on actuarial principles
- Problem: under the **Law of Ann (1672)**, widows of Church of Scotland ministers
  received only half a year's stipend on death; after that, penury
- Edinburgh life expectancy at birth likely worse than London's 23 in the late 18th century
- Their key innovation: premiums invested to grow a fund; widows paid from *returns*
  on investment, not just premiums — a capitalized reserve model
- Data: gathered from presbyteries across Scotland — "930 ministers in life at all times";
  27 die yearly, 18 leaving widows, 5 leaving only children
- Four premium tiers: £2 12s 6d to £6 11s 3d per year; annuities of £10–£25 to widows
- **Maclaurin** corrected Wallace's initial estimate of max widows (279 was too low —
  wrong to assume constant mortality for widows of different ages); used Halley's tables
- Projected fund: £18,620 at inception (1748) → £58,348 by 1765
- **Actual result: £58,347** — off by just one pound; one of the most precise actuarial
  calculations in history

> "It is experience alone & nice calculation that must determine the proportional sum
> the widow is to have after the husband's death." — Robert Wallace

- The **Scottish Ministers' Widows' Fund** was the first fund to operate on the
  **maximum principle** — capital accumulates until interest plus contributions
  suffice to pay maximum likely annuities
- Within 20 years, copycat funds sprang up: **Presbyterian Ministers' Fund of
  Philadelphia (1761)**, **English Equitable Company (1762)**,
  **United Incorporations of St Mary's Chapel (1768)**
- By 1815 insurance extended to soldiers at Waterloo (odds: ~1 in 4 of being killed)
- Fund eventually became **Scottish Widows**; taken over by Lloyds Bank in 1999;
  today manages over £100 billion

### Insurance as Institutional Investor

- Post-WWII, insurance companies allowed to invest in equities → quickly owned
  ~one third of major UK companies by mid-1950s
- Insurance premiums as % of GDP in developed economies: ~2% on eve of WWI →
  just under 10% today
- Insurance companies and pension funds became the **institutional investors**
  that now dominate global financial markets — an unintended consequence of
  the 1744 Widows' Fund model

### The Casino Advantage

- Before modern probability theory, insurers were gamblers; now they are the casino
- **Kenneth Arrow**: most people prefer a 100% chance of small loss (premium) over
  a chance of catastrophic loss — rational basis for insurance demand
- British paradox: UK spends >12% of GDP on premiums — a third more than Americans,
  nearly twice Germans — despite lower natural disaster and political risk
- Explanation: the rise and fall of the alternative, the **welfare state**

---

## Chapter 4 (cont.): From Warfare to Welfare

### The Pre-Welfare World

- Those too poor to insure faced workhouses; Marylebone Workhouse held 1,900
  in hard times — prison-like regime (oakum-picking, stone-breaking, bread and gruel)
- By the late 19th century a moral/political consensus grew: life's losers
  deserved better than the workhouse

### Bismarck's Political Insurance

- The **welfare state** was invented not in Britain but in **Germany**, and not by
  the Left but by the Right
- **Otto von Bismarck** introduced compulsory state health insurance and old-age pensions
  in 1880s — explicitly to pacify the working class
- Bismarck's logic: "A man who has a pension for his old age is . . . much easier to
  deal with than a man without that prospect"

> "Whoever embraces this idea will come to power." — Bismarck

- Britain followed in **1908**: **David Lloyd George** introduced means-tested state
  pension for over-70s; **National Health Insurance Act** followed in 1911
- Lloyd George's "**The People's Budget**" (1909) raised direct taxes to fund pensions;
  rich outnumbered by newly enfranchised poor — electoral logic paralleled Bismarck's

### Warfare Expands the Welfare State

- **WWI**: German submarines sank 7,759,000 gross tons of merchant shipping —
  private insurers excluded war risk (Lloyd's f.c.s. clause: "free of capture and seizure")
- State stepped in, effectively nationalizing merchant shipping risk;
  **Unemployment Insurance Scheme** introduced 1920 to cushion demobilization
- **WWII + Beveridge Report (1942)**: economist **William Beveridge** recommended
  assault on "Want, Disease, Ignorance, Squalor and Idleness"
- Churchill (March 1943): "national compulsory insurance for all classes for all purposes
  from the cradle to the grave"
- Arguments for state insurance: (1) covers risks private insurers won't touch;
  (2) eliminates advertising/sales costs via compulsion; (3) larger pools produce
  more stable statistical averages

### Japan: The Warfare-Welfare State

- Japan was the world's first **welfare superpower** — and its welfare state grew
  directly from military need, not social idealism
- **1923 Kantō earthquake** (7.9 magnitude): 128,000 houses destroyed, 450,000 burnt;
  total losses ~$4.6 billion vs. ¥699 million of new life insurance purchased that year alone
- 1929 Great Depression pushed rural Japan (70% agricultural, averaging 1.5 acres/farm)
  to brink of starvation
- **Kōseishō** (Welfare Ministry) approved July 1937, *two months* after war with China began —
  the timing is the argument: welfare as war preparation
- Goal: healthier citizens = healthier soldiers; slogan "all people are soldiers"
  (*kokumin kai hei*) → "all people should have insurance" (*kokumin kai hoken*)
- Health insurance coverage: 500,000 (1938) → 40 million (1944) — nearly 100-fold
- Compulsory pensions for workers introduced during war years
- Post-war, **Bunji Kondo** pushed for *bebariji no nihonhan* — "Beveridge for Japan"
- Japanese government rejected the 1950 Beveridge-style report; recommendations
  only implemented in 1961, after American occupation ended
- Japan's welfare state was not "imposed wholesale by an alien power" — it grew from
  the **warfare-welfare state** logic: social security as return for military sacrifice

<!-- pp. 181-200 -->

## Chapter 4 (continued): Safe from Risk — Japan, Friedman, Chile, and Derivatives

### Japan as Welfare Superpower

- By the late 1970s, Japan was called the **"Welfare Super-Power"** (*fukushi chōdaikoku*)
  by politician **Nakagawa Yatsuhiro** — superior to Western models
- Japan led the world in life expectancy; ~90% high school graduation rate (vs. 32% in England)
- Only Sweden was more equal; Japan had world's largest state pension fund
- Yet welfare cost was startlingly low: only 9% of national income on social security in 1975
  vs. 31% in Sweden — welfare burden roughly half that of England
- **Herman Kahn** had predicted Japan's per capita income would overtake America's by 2000
- Key insight: Japan's welfare state worked because firms and families supplemented it —
  employers reluctant to fire workers; 2/3 of Japanese over 64 still lived with their children (1990s)
- English individualism, by contrast, inclined people to game the system

### The Failure of the British Welfare State

- British welfare: social transfers rose from 2.2% of GDP (1930) → 10% (1960) → 17% (1980)
- Healthcare + social security consumed 3× more than defence as share of government spending
- Yet results were dismal: real GDP per person grew only 2.8% between 1960–1979 (vs. 8.1% in Japan)
- **Stagflation** = the result: stagnant growth + high inflation
- Root cause: marginal tax rates >100% on higher incomes; union "go slows" and "downing tools"
- The welfare state had removed capitalism's two essential incentives:
  - the carrot of serious money for strivers
  - the stick of hardship for slackers
- US suffered too: health/Medicare/social security rose from 4% to 9% of GDP 1959–1975,
  outstripping defence spending for the first time

---

### The Big Chill — Friedman, Pinochet, and the Chicago Revolution

- **Milton Friedman** won Nobel Prize in economics in 1976; famous for monetarism and
  blaming the Great Depression on Federal Reserve mistakes
- In March 1975, Friedman flew to Chile to answer: what had gone wrong with the welfare state?

#### Chile's Crisis and the Coup
- September 1973: tanks rolled through Santiago to overthrow **Salvador Allende**,
  Marxist president whose attempt to create a Communist state had ended in economic chaos
- Inflation running at 900% annually; Chile's welfare system essentially bankrupt
- Allende died defending the **Moneda Palace** with an AK-47 — a gift from **Fidel Castro**
- **General Pinochet** seized power; the junta needed an economic alternative

#### Friedman's Advice
- Friedman met Pinochet for 45 minutes; urged cutting the government deficit as the
  main cause of sky-high inflation
- A month later, the junta cut government spending by 27% and literally burned banknotes
- Friedman's deeper argument to Pinochet: Chile's problems stemmed from "forty years of
  trends toward socialism" culminating in Allende — not just a monetary problem

> 'The general line I was taking . . . was that their present difficulties were due almost
> entirely to the forty-year trend toward collectivism, socialism, and the welfare state.'
> — **Milton Friedman**

> 'The end of inflation will lead to a rapid expansion of the capital market, which will
> greatly facilitate the transfer of enterprises and activities still in the hands of the
> government to the private sector.' — Friedman's letter to Pinochet

- The *New York Times* asked: 'if the pure Chicago economic theory can be carried out in
  Chile only at the price of repression, should its authors feel some responsibility?'
- Friedman was consulting a dictator responsible for executing 2,000+ and torturing 30,000

#### The Chicago Boys
- Since the 1950s, young Chilean economists had studied at Chicago on an exchange with
  **Universidad Católica** in Santiago — returning converts to balanced budgets and free markets
- Key **Chicago Boys**: **Jorge Cauas** (finance minister), **Sergio de Castro** (his successor),
  **Miguel Kast** (labour minister, later central bank chief)
- Before Allende's fall, they had prepared a detailed reform programme called ***El Ladrillo***
  ("The Brick") — named for the thickness of the manuscript

#### José Piñera and the Pension Revolution
- The most radical reform came not from a Chicago man but from a Harvard-trained economist
- **José Piñera**, just 24 when Pinochet seized power, returned to Chile despite his moral
  qualms about the regime — he saw a once-in-a-generation opportunity
- Piñera's key insight: the **pay-as-you-go** pension system had become a pure tax,
  replacing thrift with entitlement

> 'What had begun as a system of large-scale insurance had simply become a system of
> taxation, with today's contributions being used to pay today's benefits . . . This
> "pay-as-you-go" approach had replaced the principle of thrift with the practice of
> entitlement . . . [It] destroys, at the individual level, the link between contributions
> and benefits. In other words, between effort and reward. Wherever that happens on a
> massive scale and for a long period of time, the final result is disaster.' — **José Piñera**

- 1979–1981: as Minister of Labour, Piñera created Chile's **Personal Retirement Account** (PRA) system
  - Workers opt out of state pension; redirect 10% of wages into individual accounts
  - Managed by competing private companies: ***Administradora de Fondos de Pensiones*** (**AFPs**)
  - On retirement: buy an annuity or keep contributing; disability/life insurance included
- Reform came into effect 1 May 1981 (Piñera's mischievous choice: international Labour Day)
- Workers also allowed to opt out of state health insurance into private **ISAPRE** system
- By 1990, 70%+ of workers had switched to the private PRA system

#### Results and Moral Reckoning
- Chile's economy contracted 13% in 1982 (partly due to ill-judged dollar peg in 1979)
  — temporarily vindicated left-wing critics; crisis only clearly over by 1985
- By 1990, unambiguous success: welfare reforms accounted for fully half the decline
  in government expenditure from 34% to 22% of GDP
- Pension reform boosted Chile's savings rate to 30% of GDP by 1989 — highest in Latin America
- AFPs channelled savings into domestic development; Chilean stock market rose 18× since 1987
- Annual return on PRAs: over 10%
- **Shadow side**: self-employed and casually employed not covered; many in poor areas
  (like **La Victoria**, where Che Guevara is spray-painted on walls) have no pension at all
- Government backstop: minimum pension for those who worked 20+ years; **Basic Solidarity pension**
  for those who don't qualify
- Growth rate in 15 years before Friedman's visit: 0.17%; in 15 years after: 3.28%
- Poverty rate fell from ~40% (rest of Latin America) to just 15%
- **Irony**: Chile's reform was far more radical than anything attempted in the US —
  the supposed heartland of free market economics
- Reform copied by Bolivia, El Salvador, Mexico, Peru, Colombia, Kazakhstan; British MPs
  visited Piñera for lessons

---

### The Hedged and the Unhedged

### New Threats Straining the Welfare State
- Terrorism risk: Al Qaeda openly boasted of ambition "to kill 4 million Americans"
  — **Graham Allison** (Harvard Belfer Center): nuclear terrorist attack in major city
  "more likely than not by 2014" if current policies unchanged
- A 12.5-kiloton nuclear device could kill 80,000; a 1-megaton hydrogen bomb up to 1.9 million
- Climate risk: IPCC documents rising frequency of heavy precipitation, intensifying
  tropical cyclones, rising sea levels — would amplify Katrina-style catastrophes
- 9/11 insurance losses: $30–58 billion; Katrina losses comparable
- **Key structural problem**: when private insurers are overwhelmed, the welfare state must
  step in — effectively subsidizing those who choose to live in high-risk zones

### The Hedge Fund Alternative: Ken Griffin and Citadel
- **Kenneth C. Griffin** founded **Citadel Investment Group** in Chicago;
  manages ~$16 billion; one of the world's 20 largest hedge funds
- Started trading convertible bonds from his Harvard dorm room; has "feasted on fat tails"
- Citadel offshore fund: 21% annual returns since 1998; made >$1 billion personally in 2007
  while others lost billions in the credit crunch
- Buys distressed assets from failed companies (e.g., Enron) at knockdown prices
- Griffin embodies the hedged world: Jasper Johns *False Start* for $80m; Cézanne for $60m;
  wedding at Versailles (the French château)

### Origins of Hedging and Derivatives
- Hedging originated in **agriculture**: farmers needed to lock in prices before harvest
- **Forward contracts**: bilateral agreements between seller and buyer — earliest form
- True **futures contract**: standardized, issued by an exchange, tradable
- Chicago became the birthplace of modern futures: wheat price swung from 55¢ (Jan 1858)
  to $2.88 (May 1867, partly due to Civil War) to 77¢ (March 1870) — price instability
  created demand for price certainty
- **Chicago Produce Exchange** (1874) → ancestor of today's **Chicago Mercantile Exchange**
- Currency and interest rate futures: not until the 1970s
- Stock market futures contracts: not until 1982

### Key Derivative Instruments
- **Call option**: right (not obligation) to buy at an agreed strike price — buyer profits if
  price rises above strike ("in the money")
- **Put option**: right to sell at agreed price — buyer profits if price falls
- **Interest rate swap**: two parties exchange fixed for variable rate payments
- **Credit default swap (CDS)**: protection against a company defaulting on its bonds
- **Catastrophe bond ("cat bond")**: insurer sells tail risk to hedge fund — if the specified
  disaster occurs, buyer must pay out; in return, seller earns premium. In 2006, notional
  value of weather-risk derivatives: ~$45 billion
- **OTC (over-the-counter) derivatives**: custom-made, sold by banks — total notional
  outstanding reached **$596 trillion** (December 2007); gross market value $14.5 trillion
- **Warren Buffett** famously called derivatives "financial weapons of mass destruction"
  — yet used them himself

### The Hedged vs. Unhedged Divide
- Derivatives have divided the world into two: those who **can** hedge and those who **cannot**
- Hedge funds require minimum 6–7 figure investments; management fee 2%+ of assets
  and 20% of profits (Citadel charges 8% management fee)
- Large corporations can hedge interest rate, currency, commodity, hurricane, and terrorism risk
- **Ordinary households** cannot afford to hedge — still dependent on blunt insurance
  policies and the welfare state
- Third strategy: **saving** — specifically, leveraged investment in property as a de facto
  pension and insurance policy
  - If pension falls short: "never mind, there's always the house"
  - **Flaw**: a one-way, totally unhedged bet on one asset class — the property market
  - Preview of Chapter 5: "a bet on bricks and mortar is very far from being as safe as houses"

---

## Chapter 4: Safe as Houses (continued)

### Monopoly and the Myth of Safe Property

- **Monopoly** originated as the **Landlord's Game**, invented by
  **Elizabeth Magie** to illustrate the injustice of land monopolies —
  **Parker Brothers** bought out her version in 1935 during the
  Great Depression
- Irony: the game meant to critique property ownership became a
  celebration of it — "it's smart to own property, the more you own,
  the more you make"
- By WWII, Monopoly boards were used by British intelligence to
  smuggle escape kits (maps, genuine European currencies) to POWs
  in German camps via Red Cross packages
- Core cultural claim: **"safe as houses"** — property is uniquely
  safe collateral because unlike a borrower, the house can't run away
  (Germans call it *immobile* property)
- Since 1959, total US **mortgage debt** outstanding rose 75-fold;
  by end of 2006, American owner-occupiers owed ~99% of US GDP
  vs. 38% fifty years before
- Residential investment reached a 50-year peak in 2005; ~half of
  all US GDP growth in first half of 2005 was housing-related
- **Property-owning democracy**: 65–83% of households own their
  home across the Anglosphere; a majority of voters are also
  property owners — explicitly a political model, not just economic

> "Safe as houses" — the phrase tells you all you need to know about
> why people all over the world yearn to own their own homes.

---

### The Property-owning Aristocracy

- For most of history, property ownership was the exclusive privilege
  of a hereditary elite — estates passed father to son along with
  political rights; tenants paid rent and had no say
- Pre-1832 English voting: only men owning **freehold property worth
  ≥40 shillings/year** could vote — at most 435,000 people in
  England and Wales; 370 of 514 MPs were selected by ~180
  land-owning patrons; more than a fifth of MPs were sons of peers
- Even today: ~40 million of 60 million UK acres owned by just
  **189,000 families**; the **Duke of Westminster** remains the
  third-richest man in Britain (est. £7 billion)
- Aristocratic political monopoly ended not through ideology but
  through **finance**: the mid-19th century agricultural income
  collapse destroyed the economic basis of aristocratic power

### The Fall of the Duke of Buckingham (case study)

- **Richard Plantagenet Temple-Nugent-Brydges-Chandos-Grenville,
  2nd Duke of Buckingham** — the emblematic victim of the first
  modern property crash
- Owned ~67,000 acres in England, Ireland, and Jamaica; gross income
  £72,000/year — yet by 1845 spent £109,140/year and had
  accumulated debts of **£1,027,282** (some at 15% interest)
- The Dukes of Devonshire similarly spent 40–55% of annual income
  on interest payments
- Fatal spending: refurbished Stowe House top-to-bottom for Queen
  Victoria's 1845 visit — called out an entire Regiment of Yeomanry
  at personal expense; Queen remarked: *"I have no such splendour
  in either of my two palaces"*
- August 1848: entire contents of **Stowe House** auctioned off —
  plate, wine, china, art, rare books — total proceeds £75,000;
  *The Economist* sneered he was treated "as if the Duke were a
  bankrupt earthenware dealer"
- The Duke died in 1861 living at his son's expense in the
  Great Western Hotel at Paddington railway station; his son was
  by then chairman of the London and North-western Railway Company
- **Key lesson**: in the modern world, a regular job mattered more
  than an inherited title, no matter how many acres you owned

### Why Land Failed as Security

- Agricultural income decline: grain prices fell from $3/bushel
  (1847) to 50 cents (1894) after Corn Law repeal (1846),
  falling transport costs, and global grain supply expansion
- Returns on rural property: 3.65% (1845) → 2.51% (1885)

> *The Economist*: "No security was ever relied upon with more
> implicit faith, and few have lately been found more sadly
> wanting than English land."

- As late as 1938, fewer than one-third of UK housing was
  owner-occupied — the **property-owning democracy** would be
  born in America, not Britain

---

### Home-owning Democracy

- Before the 1930s, fewer than two-fifths of American households
  were owner-occupiers; mortgages were short-term (3–5 years),
  **non-amortizing** — borrowers paid interest only, then faced
  a **balloon payment** at term end
- 1920s mortgage spread: ~200 basis points over high-grade corporate
  bonds (vs. ~50 bps in recent decades); substantial regional
  variation
- Great Depression collapse: 1932–33, over **500,000 foreclosures**;
  by mid-1933, 1,000+ mortgages foreclosed *per day*; house prices
  fell >20%; construction industry collapsed

### Detroit 1932: The Revolutionary Moment

- Detroit: automobile industry employing only half its 1929 workforce
  at half the wages — the human face of Depression misery
- **7 March 1932**: 5,000 unemployed Ford workers marched to the
  River Rouge plant in Dearborn; police and security men opened fire;
  **5 workers killed**; 60,000 sang 'The Internationale' at their
  funeral — Communist Party accused **Edsel Ford** of allowing
  a massacre
- **Diego Rivera** (Communist, Trotskyite, expelled from Mexican
  Communist Party) was commissioned by Edsel Ford / Detroit
  Institute of Arts to paint murals showing Detroit as cooperation,
  not conflict — at a cost of ~$25,000
- Rivera's actual vision: workers laboring while property owners
  "just stood and watched"; murals unveiled 1933 caused outrage —
  Dr. George H. Derry: *"Rivera has perpetrated a heartless hoax
  on his capitalist employer, Edsel Ford... a Communist manifesto"*
- Rivera's next commission (Rockefeller Center for **John D.
  Rockefeller Jr.**): destroyed after he insisted on including
  a portrait of Lenin and slogans: "Down With Imperialistic Wars!",
  "Workers Unite!", "Free Money!"

### The New Deal Housing Revolution

- **Franklin D. Roosevelt**'s answer to revolutionary threat:
  the **property-owning democracy** as antidote to communism
- Key New Deal housing institutions:
  - **Home Owners' Loan Corporation**: refinanced mortgages on
    longer terms (up to 15 years)
  - **Federal Home Loan Bank Board** (est. 1932): oversaw
    **Savings and Loans (thrifts)** — mutual associations
    taking deposits and lending to homebuyers
  - **Federal deposit insurance**: Roosevelt's guarantee that
    S&L deposits were safe even if borrowers defaulted
  - **Federal Housing Administration (FHA)**: provided federally
    backed insurance for mortgage lenders; encouraged large
    (up to 80% LTV), long (20-year), fully **amortized**,
    low-interest loans
- FHA standardized the long-term mortgage + created national
  inspection/valuation system → foundation for a **national
  secondary market**
- **1938**: **Federal National Mortgage Association ("Fannie Mae")**
  authorized to issue bonds and buy mortgages from local S&Ls
  — S&Ls restricted by **Regulation Q** (deposit rate ceiling)
  and geography (could not lend >50 miles from office)
- Result: home ownership rate rose from 40% → 60% by 1960;
  the modern American suburb was "born here"

> *It's a Wonderful Life* (Frank Capra, 1946) as propaganda for
> the thrift/S&L model — George Bailey (Jimmy Stewart):
> "It's deep in the race for a man to want his own roof and
> walls and fireplace, and we're helping him get those things
> in our shabby little office."

### Red-lining: The Hidden Exclusion

- The property-owning democracy was racially exclusionary from
  the start — in 1941 a Detroit developer built a **six-foot
  wall** across 8 Mile Road to qualify for FHA loans (loans only
  on the white side of the wall)
- Federal Home Loan Bank Board maps **color-coded** neighborhoods:
  A/B/C = mainly white; **D = red = predominantly black** →
  origin of the term **"red-lining"**
- In the 1950s: 1 in 5 black mortgage borrowers paid ≥8%;
  virtually no whites paid >7% — "the hidden financial dimension
  of the Civil Rights struggle"
- **Detroit riot, 23 July 1967**: 43 killed, 467 injured, 7,200
  arrested, 3,000 buildings burned — partly rooted in rage at
  mortgage discrimination; required regular army with tanks
- Political response: **1968** — Fannie Mae split into:
  - **Ginnie Mae** (Government National Mortgage Association):
    served poor borrowers, military veterans
  - Rechartered **Fannie Mae**: privately owned **GSE**,
    bought conventional + government-guaranteed mortgages
  - **1970**: **Freddie Mac** (Federal Home Loan Mortgage
    Corporation) created to compete in secondary market
- **Community Reinvestment Act (1977)**: banks under statutory
  pressure to lend to poorer minority communities
- S&L operators' comfortable world: the **"3-6-3 rule"** —
  pay 3% on deposits, lend at 6%, be on the golf course by 3pm

### Britain's Slower Path

- Post-war Britain: both Conservatives and Labour agreed state
  should *provide* housing — Harold Macmillan targeted 300,000
  (later 400,000) new houses/year; 1959–64 roughly a third of
  new houses built by local councils (rising to half under Labour)
- As late as 1971, fewer than half of British homes were
  owner-occupied
- **Thatcher's revolution**: introduced **MIRAS** (Mortgage Interest
  Relief At Source) on first £30,000 of mortgage; sold council
  houses at "bargain-basement prices" to 1.5 million working-class
  families → owner-occupier share: 54% (1981) → 67% (1991);
  stock of owner-occupied properties: 11 million → 17 million+
- US mortgage interest deduction existed since **1913** (inception
  of federal income tax); Reagan called it "part of the American dream"

### The Inflationary Free Lunch (and its aftermath)

- 1960s–70s: inflation rates rose above interest rates → debtors
  got a **free lunch** — real value of debt and interest payments
  declined
- Mid-1970s: homebuyers expected 12% inflation by 1980;
  lenders offered 30-year fixed loans at ≤9% → lenders were
  effectively paying people to borrow
- Property prices roughly **trebled** 1963–79 while consumer
  prices rose only 2.5x
- The sting: the same governments championing property-owning
  democracy also believed in **price stability** → raised interest
  rates → set up one of the biggest property booms and busts in history

---

### From S&L to Subprime

- **Savings and Loans (S&Ls)**: America's property-owning democracy
  rested on these mutual associations — deposits insured up to
  $40,000 for a premium of just 1/12 of 1% of deposits;
  constrained: could only lend within 50 miles; Regulation Q
  capped deposit rates at 5.5%
- Late 1970s double punch: **13.3% inflation** (1979) + sharply
  rising interest rates under **Paul Volcker** (Fed Chair)
  → S&Ls simultaneously losing money on fixed-rate mortgages
  AND hemorrhaging deposits to money market funds
- Carter + Reagan administrations' response: **deregulation** —
  S&Ls could now invest in commercial property, stocks, junk bonds
- Reagan on deregulation: *"All in all, I think we hit the jackpot"*
  — setting the stage for the S&L scandal

<!-- pp. 221-240 -->

## Chapter 4 (continued): The Return of Risk — S&L Crisis, Securitization & Subprime

### The S&L Fraud Epidemic

- S&Ls after deregulation: could issue credit cards, pay any interest rate,
  raise money via brokered "jumbo" $100,000 CDs — yet deposits still
  federally insured (max raised from $40k to $100k)
- Classic **moral hazard**: nothing to lose, everything to gamble with
- **William Crawford** (CA Savings & Loan Commissioner) principle:
  "The best way to rob a bank is to own one"
- Dallas nexus of fraud: **Don Dixon** (Vernon S&L, nicknamed "Vermin"),
  **Ed McBirney** of Sunbelt ("Gunbelt"), **Tyrell Barker** of State S&L
  ("You bring the dirt, I bring the money")
- **Mario Renda**, NY Teamsters broker, allegedly laundered Mafia funds
  through S&Ls; advertised in NYT: "MONEY FOR RENT: BORROWING
  OBSTACLES NEUTRALIZED BY HAVING US DEPOSIT FUNDS WITH
  YOUR LOCAL BANK"

### Danny Faulkner and Empire Savings & Loan

- **Empire S&L** chairman Spencer Blain teamed with mayor of Garland
  James Toler and high-school dropout developer **Danny Faulkner**
- Faulkner's specialty: "the flip" — buy land for peanuts, instantly
  resell at vastly inflated prices to investors borrowing from Empire
  - One parcel: bought for $3 million, sold days later for $47 million
- Empire's assets grew from $12M to $257M in two years; $309M by Jan 1984
- By 1984, Dallas I-30 corridor lined with "see-through" office buildings
  (empty, still under construction) funded by federally insured deposits
- Faulkner flew investors over properties by helicopter — without landing
- **Edwin J. Gray** (Federal Home Loan Bank Board) ordered Empire's closure
  March 14, 1984; cost to **FSLIC** was $300 million
- By 1986 the FSLIC itself was insolvent

### Scale of the S&L Catastrophe

- In 1991 Faulkner, Blain, Toler convicted of civil racketeering; looted
  $165M; each sentenced to 20 years
- ~500 S&Ls collapsed; ~500 more merged under the **Resolution Trust
  Corporation** (created by Congress to clean up)
- Near half of insolvent institutions had "fraud and potentially criminal
  conduct by insiders"
- By May 1991: 764 charged, 550 convicted, 326 jailed; $8M in fines
- **Total cost 1986–1995: $153 billion (~3% of GDP); taxpayers bore $124B**
  — most expensive financial crisis since the Depression

> "The most widespread, reckless and fraudulent era in this nation's banking history."
> — Edwin Gray on the S&L crisis

---

### The Birth of Securitization

- As S&Ls collapsed, **Salomon Brothers** bond traders saw opportunity
- **Lewis Ranieri** (started in Salomon mailroom) bought desperate S&Ls'
  mortgages at rock-bottom prices
- Key innovation: bundle thousands of mortgages together as backing for
  new securities — **mortgage-backed securities (MBS)**; interest payments
  subdivided into "strips" with different maturities and credit risks
- First **collateralized mortgage obligation (CMO)**: June 1983
- Process called **securitization** — transformed Wall Street; anonymous
  transactions replaced personal lending relationships

> "It was the dawn of a new era in American finance."

- Most mortgages carried implicit government guarantee via **Fannie Mae**,
  **Freddie Mac**, or **Ginnie Mae** — so MBS could be marketed as
  near-government bonds ("investment grade")
- GSE-backed MBS grew from $200M (1980) to $4 trillion (2007)
- In 1980: 10% of home mortgage market securitized; by 2007: 56%
- Contrast with *It's a Wonderful Life* model: Jimmy Stewart knew his
  depositors AND his debtors — in a securitized market the interest payer
  and the ultimate recipient are strangers, thousands of miles apart

---

### Property vs. Stocks — The "Safe as Houses" Myth

- Common English-speaking assumption: property is a one-way bet, the
  surest path to wealth
- Data challenge: $100,000 into US property in Q1 1987 → ~$275K–$299K
  by Q1 2007 (trebled). Same $100K into S&P 500 with reinvested
  dividends → **$772,000** — more than double
- UK: £100K into property 1987 → quadrupled; into FTSE All-Share
  (with dividends) → **nearly seven times richer**
- Three key disadvantages of housing vs. stocks:
  1. **Depreciation** — houses wear out, stocks don't need new roofs
  2. **Illiquidity** — expensive to convert to cash quickly
  3. **Volatility** — housing *less* volatile than stocks, but not
     immune to crashes: Britain 1989–95, average prices fell 18%
     (37% in real terms); London: -47%; Japan 1990–2000: -60%
- **Case-Shiller composite 20** index: peaked July 2006; down 15% by
  Feb 2008; annualized decline of 13% — not seen since early 1930s
- "Houses are not a uniquely safe investment. Their prices can go down
  as well as up."
- House prices are "sticky" downward (sellers resist cutting asking price)
  → glut of unsold properties; also reduces labour mobility, slowing recovery

---

### Subprime: Detroit as Ground Zero

- Ferguson visits **Detroit's West Outer Drive** — once a prosperous
  middle-class street, now ground zero of the subprime crisis
- "Subprime" mortgages targeted borrowers with poor/patchy credit histories
  — too risky for Fannie Mae's approval
- Features designed to maximize initial affordability, hide true cost:
  - **Adjustable-rate mortgages (ARMs)** — rate varies with short-term
    benchmark
  - **Interest-only** loans (no principal repayment), 100% loan-to-value
  - **"Teaser" periods** — artificially low rates for first 2 years,
    then steep resets
  - Example: 9.75% for 2 years, then **9.125 points over LIBOR**
    — a catastrophic jump in year 3
- 2006: subprime lenders injected **>$1 billion** into 22 Detroit ZIP codes
- 48235 ZIP code (includes 5100 block of West Outer Drive): subprime
  mortgages = **more than half** of all loans 2002–2006; 7 of 26 households
  on 5100 block took subprime loans
- Most subprime volume was **refinancing**, not new purchases — borrowers
  using homes as cash machines to pay credit card debts or buy consumer
  goods
- By 2005: 69% of US households were homeowners (vs. 64% ten years earlier);
  ~half that increase attributed to subprime boom
- **Racial disparity**: 55% of Black and Latino borrowers in metro Boston
  had subprime mortgages (2005) vs. 13% of white borrowers;
  Washington Mutual: 75%+ of Black/Latino borrowers classed subprime
  vs. 17% of white borrowers

### Political Promotion of Home Ownership

- **Alan Greenspan** endorsed ARMs in a 2004 speech (later retracted),
  but Ferguson argues monetary policy was not the primary driver
- **President George W. Bush**, Oct 2002: "We want everybody in America
  to own their own home"
  - Challenged lenders to create 5.5 million new minority homeowners
  - Signed **American Dream Downpayment Act** (2003) — subsidized
    first-time purchases for lower-income buyers
  - Lenders encouraged not to require full documentation from subprime
    borrowers
  - **HUD** pressured Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac to support subprime market
- **Henry Louis "Skip" Gates Jr.** (Harvard, Nov 2007 NYT): praised
  homeownership as solution to Black poverty, invoking **Margaret Thatcher**'s
  UK council house sales (1.5M tenants → homeowners in 1980s)
- **Beanie Self** (Memphis community leader) identified the fatal flaw:
  "The American Dream is home ownership, and... we are not really prepared
  for it. People don't realize you have a real estate industry, an appraisal
  industry, a mortgage industry now that can really push to put people into
  houses that a lot of times they really can't afford."

---

### The CDO Machine and Global Risk Distribution

- Subprime lenders didn't hold the loans — pocketed commissions at signing,
  then resold in bulk to Wall Street
- Banks bundled loans into **residential mortgage-backed securities (RMBS)**
  → further repackaged as **collateralized debt obligations (CDOs)**
- CDO alchemy: risky loans → triple-A rated investment-grade securities
  (with certification from **Moody's** or **Standard & Poor's**)
- Risk ostensibly spread globally — from US pension funds to Australian
  public health networks to Norwegian Arctic Circle municipalities
  - **Rana, Hemnes, Hattjelldal, and Narvik** (Norway): invested $120M
    of taxpayers' money in CDOs backed by American subprime mortgages
- Fatal flaw: "Securitization was having the effect of allocating risk
  'to those best able to bear it.' Only later did it turn out that risk
  was being allocated to those least able to understand it."
- Brokers who knew the loans were toxic bore the least risk — could make
  a **100% loan-to-value NINJA loan** ("No Income No Job or Assets")
  and sell it same day

### The Crisis Unfolds

- Fed raised short-term rates from 1% to 5.25% → average mortgage rates
  up ~1.3 percentage points (5.34% to 6.66%)
- When teaser periods expired and ARMs reset, defaults cascaded:
  by March 2007, ~1 in 3 subprime mortgages in 48235 ZIP were 60+ days
  in arrears (on verge of foreclosure)
- Memphis: 1 in 4 households had received foreclosure notice by summer 2007;
  Center for Responsible Lending predicted 2.4 million foreclosures
  (likely an underestimate)
- By May 2008: 1.8M mortgages in default; ~9M households in negative equity
  (1 in 10 single-family homes); 11% of subprime ARMs in foreclosure
- Crédit Suisse estimate: total foreclosures could reach **6.5 million**,
  potentially evicting 8.4% of all US homeowners

### Contagion: From CDOs to Global Crisis

- Summer 2007: CDO crisis spreads through global credit markets
- **HSBC** (Feb 2007): admitted heavy losses on US mortgages — first major signal
- True crisis start: **Bear Stearns** hedge funds asked by **Merrill Lynch**
  to post additional collateral; Bear bailed one fund, let the other collapse
- Ratings agencies then downgraded scores of RMBS CDOs; institutions
  holding them suddenly faced huge losses
- Banks had disguised exposure by parking assets in off-balance-sheet
  **conduits** and **SIVs** (strategic investment vehicles) — funded
  by short-term commercial paper and overnight interbank loans
- **Counterparty risk** fears → credit markets seized
- August 2007 liquidity crisis: **American Home Mortgage** filed bankruptcy;
  **BNP Paribas** suspended three mortgage investment funds;
  **Countrywide Financial** drew down entire $11B credit line
- Final tally (to date of writing): **Northern Rock** nationalized;
  **Bear Stearns** sold cheaply to JPMorgan in Fed-underwritten deal;
  numerous hedge funds wound up; bank write-downs ≥$318B;
  anticipated total losses >$1 trillion
- "The subprime butterfly had flapped its wings and triggered a global hurricane."

### Fannie Mae's Fatal Irony

- Crisis threatened the very institution that created the property-owning
  democracy: **Fannie Mae** (with Freddie and Ginnie)
- Between 1955 and 2006: government-underwritten share of non-farm mortgages
  fell from 35% to 5%, but GSEs' share of mortgages held rose from 4% to
  43% (peak 2003)
- Fannie/Freddie had only $84B capital against $1.7T in assets plus
  $2.8T in guaranteed RMBS — capital ratio ~5%
- OFHEO had been pushing them to acquire even more RMBS by relaxing
  capital rules — a disaster in waiting

---

## "As Safe as Housewives" — Property Rights & Development

### Hernando de Soto's "Mystery of Capital"

- **Quilmes** slum, Buenos Aires outskirts: appears poor but represents
  enormous latent wealth
- **Hernando de Soto** (Peruvian economist): total value of real estate
  occupied by world's poor = **$9.3 trillion** — roughly equal to total
  market cap of all listed companies in the world's top 20 economies;
  ~90× all foreign aid 1970–2000
- Core problem: squatters lack **secure legal title** → property cannot
  be used as collateral → can't borrow → can't start businesses
- **"Dead capital"** — like water trapped in a high Andean lake, full of
  potential energy but unable to flow
- Bureaucratic barriers are enormous: Argentina now ~30 days to register
  property; Bangladesh/Haiti ~300 days; Peru (when de Soto tested):
  6 years 11 months, 52 government offices; Philippines: 168-step,
  13–25 year process involving 53 agencies
  - English-speaking world: 2 days to 3 weeks

> "Property law is not a silver bullet, but it is the missing link...
> Without property law, you will never be able to accomplish other reforms
> in a sustainable manner." — Hernando de Soto

- Additional argument: property rights → democracy, because a market-
  oriented property system requires democratic accountability
- **Bill Clinton** called de Soto "probably the greatest living economist";
  **Vladimir Putin** praised his work; won **Cato Institute Milton
  Friedman Prize** (2004); advised governments in Egypt, El Salvador,
  Ghana, Haiti, Honduras, Kazakhstan, Mexico, Philippines, Tanzania
- Enemies: **Shining Path** (Maoist) tried to assassinate him in 1992
  (bomb killed three people); critics linked him to disgraced President
  **Alberto Fujimori**

### The Quilmes Experiment — Does Title Actually Work?

- In 1981, 1,800 families occupied wasteland near Buenos Aires, defying
  the military junta; post-democracy government expropriated original
  owners and granted legal title to squatters
- Only 8 of 13 landowners accepted compensation; others fought legal
  battles — so some squatters got title, others didn't
- Natural experiment result: **property title changed attitudes** —
  owners 34% more likely than squatters to say "money is important for
  happiness" (more individualist/materialist)
- BUT: only **4% of Quilmes title-holders** secured a mortgage
- Peru: after 1.2M urban buildings legalized (post-1996 Commission for
  Formalization of Informal Property), only ~25% of Lima households
  awarded titles in 1998–99 had obtained any loan by 2002
- Cambodia: granting title simply encouraged developers/speculators to
  buy out or evict poor residents
- Key insight against de Soto: **"It's not owning property that gives
  you security; it just gives your creditors security. Real security
  comes from having a steady income."**
- Home ownership may not be key to wealth generation — and may not be
  the solution to developing-world poverty

### Microfinance as Alternative — Betty Flores and Pro Mujer

- **Betty Flores**, El Alto, Bolivia (town above La Paz): indigenous woman
  running coffee stall at street market; client of **Pro Mujer**
  microfinance organization
- Took loan to expand her coffee business — her husband (mechanic) had
  been unable to do the same; business thriving, putting daughters
  through school
- Flores has modest savings, owns no home — not a "good credit risk"
  by conventional standards
- Key revelation of **microfinance** in developing countries: **women
  are actually better credit risks than men**, with or without property
  as collateral — contradicts centuries of prejudice (until 1970s,
  women systematically rated as worse credit risks)

<!-- pp. 241-260 -->

## Chapter 5 (conclusion): Safe as Houses

### Microfinance — Creditworthiness as a Female Trait
- Historical credit discrimination: married US women denied credit even when
  employed; credit was "emphatically male"
- **Muhammad Yunus** (Nobel Prize winner) discovered women's creditworthiness
  while studying rural poverty in Bangladesh
- **Grameen Bank** ("Village Bank"), founded 1983 in village of Jobra:
  - ~7.5 million borrowers, nearly all women, no collateral required
  - Borrowers organized in five-member groups (**koota**), meeting weekly,
    informally sharing loan repayment responsibility
  - Made >$3 billion in microloans; initially aid-funded, now self-sustaining
    and profitable (~$650 billion in deposits by Jan 2007)
- **Pro Mujer** (founded 1990 by Lynne Patterson and Carmen Velasco): major
  South American imitator; loans start ~$200 for 3 months, used for livestock
  or micro-businesses
- Pattern repeated from Bolivia's El Alto to slums of Nairobi to Andhra Pradesh
  to Castlemilk, Glasgow — credit unions as antidote to loan sharks

### Limits of Microfinance
- Not a "holy grail" — ~2/5 of world population outside financial system
  entirely, no bank accounts, much less credit
- Giving loans alone doesn't automatically end poverty
- **Predatory microfinance**: some firms charge 80–125% interest annually,
  justified by administrative costs of tiny loans — rates "worthy of loan sharks"
- **Hernando de Soto's** property rights prescription similarly not a cure-all

### Housing Bubble — The "Home Bias" Problem
- **Robert Shiller**: house prices rose far above rental income or construction
  cost justification — "widespread perception that houses are a great investment"
  created a "classic speculative bubble" via same feedback mechanism as stock
  bubbles since John Law
- Glasgow 2007: house prices fell 2.1%; Edinburgh fell 5.8%
- **Home bias** in finance = tendency to keep money in domestic assets; but
  real home bias = investing nearly all wealth in one's own home
- Housing = two-thirds of typical US household's portfolio (higher elsewhere)
- Political encouragement of home ownership distorts capital markets — forces
  people to bet everything on a single leveraged, illiquid asset
- Key principle: financial security requires **diversified portfolio**; borrow
  against future earnings but maintain sustainable spread between borrowing
  costs and investment returns; keep sustainable debt-to-income balance
- Final question posed: the US itself — the "subprime superpower" — has
  violated these same rules at national scale

---

## Chapter 6: From Empire to Chimerica

### The Decoupling Question
- Conventional wisdom before 1997–98 Asian Crisis: financial crises happen on
  the periphery (emerging markets), not the core
- But 21st-century threats have come from the core: dot-com bubble (S&P 500
  fell ~50% after Aug 2000, didn't recover until May 2007); then subprime
  crisis in credit markets, not stocks
- **Jim O'Neill** (Goldman Sachs Head of Global Research): Asia "decoupling"
  from US despite credit crunch — China-led world potentially independent of
  American cycle
- If O'Neill correct: end of ~100+ year era when English-speakers (Britain,
  then US) set global financial tempo
- **BRICs** (Brazil, Russia, India, China) projection: China to overtake US
  GDP originally estimated ~2040; revised to **2027**
- China per capita GDP growth: compound annual rate of **8.4%** over 30 years
- Challenges acknowledged: demographic time bomb (one-child policy),
  environmental costs, inflationary pressure (stocks 2007, food prices 2008)

### The Great Divergence
- 300–400 years ago: per capita incomes in West and East roughly equal
  - Ming China more sophisticated than early Massachusetts in many ways
  - Beijing was world's largest city; Admiral **Zheng He's** treasure ship
    dwarfed Columbus's *Santa Maria*
- Between 1700–1950: "**great divergence**" in living standards
  - By 1820: US income ~2x China; by 1870: ~5x; by 1913: ~10x; by 1950: ~22x
  - US avg annual per capita GDP growth 1820–1950: **1.57%**; China: **-0.24%**
  - In 1973: average Chinese income at best 1/20th of American
  - As of 2006: US-to-China per capita income ratio still **22.9:1**

### Why China Fell Behind — A Financial Hypothesis
- Two "strokes of luck" China missed (conventional resource argument):
  1. **Ghost acres**: Caribbean sugar colonies relieved agricultural pressure
     on Europe that would have caused Chinese-style diminishing returns
  2. **Proximity of coalfields** to industrial development sites
- But Ferguson's key argument: **China's problems were as much financial as
  resource-based**
  - Unitary empire precluded **fiscal competition** that drove financial
    innovation in Renaissance Europe
  - Empire could finance deficits by printing money → discouraged development
    of European-style capital markets
  - Coinage readily available (trade surplus) → fewer incentives for commercial
    bills, bonds, equities
  - Modern financial institutions arrived in China only in late 19th century
    as part of **Western imperialism** — always vulnerable to patriotic backlash

### Globalization Is Not New
- Pre-1914 globalization was as extensive as today's in key dimensions:
  - Trade in goods reached ~same share of global output in 3 decades before 1914
  - International migration larger relative to world population:
    >14% of US population foreign-born in 1910 vs. <12% in 2003
  - Net foreign investment (rich → poor countries) was **much larger** in
    earlier period than in the 1990s
- In 1913: 25% of world's stock of foreign capital in countries with per capita
  income ≤1/5 of US; by 1997: only **5%**

---

### Globalization and Armageddon

### The Problem of Overseas Investment: Information and Enforcement
- Key problem then and now: investors in London or New York cannot monitor
  what a foreign government or manager does an ocean away
- Non-Western countries had unreliable legal systems and differing accounting
  rules; no mechanism to enforce debt contracts across borders
- Solution in first era of globalization: **impose European rule**

### The Opium War — Finance Backed by Force
- **William Jardine** and **James Matheson**: Scottish merchants who set up
  trading company in Guangzhou (Canton) 1832
  - Main business: importing government-produced opium from India
  - Opium banned by Emperor **Yongzheng** in 1729 for social costs
- March 1839: Imperial official **Lin Zexu** arrived in Canton; blockaded
  opium warehouses until ~20,000 chests (value: £2 million) surrendered and
  destroyed at sea
- Jardine (known to Chinese as "**Iron-Headed Old Rat**") lobbied Foreign
  Secretary **Viscount Palmerston** in London; persuaded him Chinese "war
  junks" would be no match for British naval force
- Feb 1840: Palmerston gave the order; June 1840: naval preparations complete

> "The Qing Empire was about to feel the full force of history's most
> successful narco-state: the British Empire." — Ferguson

- **First Opium War** results:
  - **Convention of Chuenpi** (Jan 1841): Hong Kong ceded to Britain
    (repudiated by Emperor; reaffirmed by **Treaty of Nanking** 1842)
  - Five **treaty ports** opened: Canton, Amoy, Foochow, Ningbo, Shanghai
  - Principle of **extraterritoriality**: British subjects immune from Chinese
    law in these cities
- For China: era of humiliation — drug addiction exploded; **Taiping Rebellion**
  killed 20–40 million; Confucian beliefs destabilized by Christian missionaries
- For Jardine Matheson: Hong Kong became entrepôt; by early 1900s the firm
  owned breweries, cotton mills, insurance company, ferry company, railways
  (Kowloon-Canton line, 1907–11)

### Victorian Globalization — The Scale of British Overseas Investment
- Rothschild ledgers show a single page listing bonds from Chile, Egypt,
  Germany, Hungary, Italy, Japan, Norway, Spain, Turkey + 11 railway securities
- By 1909, British retail investors could buy **Henry Lowenfeld's**
  *Investment: An Exact Science* (2s 6d) recommending "Geographical
  Distribution of Capital" to reduce speculation

> "It required scarcely any effort for a Londoner of moderate means to
> 'adventure his wealth in the natural resources and new enterprises of any
> quarter of the world.'" — **Keynes**, *Economic Consequences of the Peace*

- By 1914: ~40 foreign stock exchanges; London Stock Exchange listed bonds
  from 57 sovereign/colonial governments
- British capital allocation: 45% to US/Canada/Antipodes; 20% Latin America;
  16% Asia; 13% Africa; 6% rest of Europe
- 1865–1914: **majority** of British capital raised went overseas; <1/3
  invested in UK itself
- By 1913: $158 billion in securities worldwide; ~$45 billion (28%) held
  internationally; 48% of LSE listings were foreign bonds
- Gross foreign assets 1913: ~**150% of UK GDP**; current account surplus
  hit **9% of GDP** in 1913 — "a British savings glut"

### Empire as Credit Guarantee
- 2/5 to 1/2 of all British overseas investment went to **British-controlled
  colonies**; substantial additional amounts to countries like Argentina and
  Brazil under British informal influence
- **Colonial Loans Act (1899)** and **Colonial Stock Act (1900)**: gave
  colonial bonds same **trustee status** as British consols — eligible for
  Trustee Savings Banks
- Victorian "public goods" of liberal imperialism: rule of law, British-style
  property rights, relatively non-corrupt administration
- British rule = implicit "**no default**" guarantee; uncertainty limited to
  expected duration of British rule
- Key example: £74 million invested in Chinese securities 1865–1914 (small
  share of £4 billion total) — secured because Britain controlled Hong Kong
  **and** Chinese Imperial Maritime Customs (collecting port duties earmarked
  for interest payments)
- But even imperial power couldn't prevent: Sino-Japanese War 1894–5, Boxer
  Rebellion 1900, Qing dynasty revolution 1911 — each hit foreign investors

### The Pre-1914 Golden Age — and Its Illusions
- Communications transformed: by 1911, telegraphic message New York→London
  took **30 seconds**; cost was **0.5%** of 1866 level
- Gold standard nearly universal by 1908 → reduced exchange rate risk
- Emerging market spreads narrowed dramatically; by 1913 almost no sovereign/
  colonial bond traded more than **2 percentage points** above British consols
- Consol yield itself was at historic nadir of 2.25% (rose just over 1pp by 1914)
- *The Future of War* (1898): **Ivan Bloch** (6 volumes) argued modern war
  technologically too destructive — would end in "bankruptcy of nations"
- **Norman Angell**, *The Great Illusion* (1910): major war economically
  impossible due to "the delicate interdependence of our credit-built finance"
- Spring 1914: international commission chairman declared great powers had
  "discovered the obvious truth that the richest country has the most to lose
  by war, and each country wishes for peace above all things"
- **Henry Noel Brailsford**, *The War of Steel and Gold*: "there will be no
  more wars among the six great powers"

### The 1914 Financial Crisis — Globalization's End
- Financial markets initially **shrugged off** assassination of **Archduke
  Franz Ferdinand** (28 June 1914); not until 22 July did serious anxiety emerge
- When war likelihood grasped: liquidity sucked out of world economy as if
  "the bottom had dropped out of a bath"
- Cascade of failures:
  1. **Shipping insurance premiums** spiked
  2. Bond/stock prices fell as investors shifted to cash
  3. European investors sold Russian securities; Americans followed
  4. Exchange rates destabilized: sterling and franc surged; ruble and dollar slumped
  5. By 30 July: **panic** on most financial markets
  6. **Jobbers** (leveraged equity dealers) bankrupted as stock values fell
     below debt values (notably **Derenberg & Co.**)
  7. **Commercial bill brokers** owed funds by continental counterparties
  8. **Acceptance houses** (merchant banks) liable on accepted bills
  9. **Joint-stock banks** called in loans → deepened credit crunch
- Most remarkable consequence: **closure of world's major stock exchanges**
  for up to five months
  - Vienna closed 27 July; all continental European exchanges by 30 July
  - London and New York closed 31 July
  - London Stock Exchange didn't reopen until **4 January 1915** — first
    closure since its founding in 1773
  - NYSE: limited trading (bonds for cash only) from 28 November; fully
    unrestricted trading not until **1 April 1915**
  - Ferguson's verdict: "No act of state-sponsored terrorism has had greater
    financial consequences than Gavrilo Princip's in 1914"

### Government Response to 1914 Crisis
- **Gold standard exacerbated** the crisis: Bank of England raised discount
  rates to deter capital repatriation, draining gold reserves
- Emergency measures (Britain): bank holiday extended; payments on bills of
  exchange postponed by royal proclamation; month-long moratorium on most
  payments; Chancellor guaranteed Bank of England against losses on pre-war
  accepted bills → government rescue of discount houses
- US: emergency currency issued under **Aldrich-Vreeland Act of 1908**
- Russia and others simply suspended gold convertibility
- "Then, as now, the authorities reacted to a liquidity crisis by printing money"
- Scale of intervention unprecedented in purely financial crises; war justified
  measures inconceivable in peacetime — including (per one Conservative peer)
  "the release of the bankers . . . from all liability"

<!-- pp. 261-280 -->

## Chapter 5 (continued): Safe as Houses / WWI Financial Aftermath

### The Cost of the Great War to Investors

- London stock market closed at outbreak of WWI; already down 7% before
  fighting began
- By end of 1914: Russian bonds -8.8%, British consols -9.3%,
  French *rentes* -13.2%, Austrian bonds -23%
- **Patrick Shaw-Stewart** of Barings: "one of the most terrific things
  London had been up against since finance existed"
- Investors who held **gilt-edged securities** through the war suffered
  inflation-adjusted losses of -46% by 1920; real returns on British
  equities -27%
- Hyperinflation in Germany: by 1923 holders of all German securities
  had lost everything
- **Bolshevik regime** defaulted on Russian bonds February 1918;
  Russian 5% bonds (1906 vintage) traded at <45% of face value;
  worthless by 1930s
- Habsburg, Ottoman, and Romanov empires all collapsed — gold-denominated
  bonds in those currencies became worthless too

### Collapse of the First Globalization

- Post-WWI: currency crises, defaults, reparations disputes, Depression
  → countries imposed **exchange and capital controls** + protectionist
  tariffs
- China declared bankruptcy 19 October 1921; defaults spread from
  Shanghai to Santiago, Moscow to Mexico City
- By end of 1930s most states had imposed restrictions on trade,
  migration, and investment — some achieved near-total **autarky**
- Key insight: financial markets were flashing green until the very eve
  of WWI — "abundant liquidity and the passage of time" blinded investors
  to geopolitical risk
- It had been 34 years since the last major European war (1870); the
  "short war" illusion prevailed in financial circles even more than
  military ones

> "The first era of financial globalization took at least a generation
> to achieve. But it was blown apart in a matter of days. And it would
> take more than two generations to repair the damage done by the guns
> of August 1914."

---

## Section: Economic Hit Men

### Bretton Woods and the Controlled Globalization (1944–1971)

- From 1930s to late 1960s, international finance "slumbered"
- **Arthur Bloomfield** (American economist, 1946): capital controls
  now "highly respectable doctrine" — a *volte-face* from pre-war
  free capital movement
- **Bretton Woods** conference, July 1944: Allies devised new financial
  architecture — trade liberalized but capital movements restricted
- **Keynes**, architect of Bretton Woods: "control of capital movements"
  would be a "permanent feature of the post-war system"
- Exchange rates fixed; **dollar** replaced gold as international
  reserve currency (dollar nominally convertible to gold; gold sat
  "immobile but totemic" at Fort Knox)
- **The Impossible Trinity (trilemma)**: a country can choose only 2 of 3:
  1. Free cross-border capital movements
  2. Fixed exchange rate
  3. Independent monetary policy for domestic objectives
- Under Bretton Woods, Western countries chose options 2 and 3
- 1963 US **Interest Equalization Act** expressly discouraged Americans
  from investing in foreign securities — capital controls tightening,
  not loosening

### Two Sisters: IMF and World Bank

- Bretton Woods created the **IMF** (regulate exchange rates) and
  **International Bank for Reconstruction and Development** (later
  World Bank — rebuild war-shattered countries)
- **Robert Zoellick** (World Bank President): "Free trade would be
  revived. But free capital flows were out."
- Marshall Plan aid (1948–1952) revived Western Europe via
  government-to-government flows — the only sanctioned form of
  international capital movement
- Third World aid programmes modeled on Marshall Plan largely failed:
  US aid became hedged with political/military conditions; capital
  injection per **Walt Rostow**'s models was not the solution for
  most African, Asian, and Latin American economies; much was wasted
  or stolen

### Nixon Shock and the Return of Hot Money

- Late 1960s: US deficits prompted French complaints that Washington
  collected **seigniorage** from reserve currency status — like
  medieval monarchs debasing coinage
- **Jacques Rueff** (de Gaulle's adviser) had warned of exactly this
  inflationary consequence
- 1971: **Nixon** severed dollar-gold convertibility → death knell for
  Bretton Woods
- 1973 Arab oil embargo: central banks accommodated price shock with
  easy credit → inflationary crisis
- 1970s: Western banks recycled **petrodollar** surpluses by lending
  to Latin America; Latin American borrowings grew from $75 billion
  (1975) to $315 billion (1982)
- August 1982: **Mexico** declared inability to service its debt;
  entire continent on brink of default

### Washington Consensus and Conditionality

- IMF and World Bank replaced the gunboat as enforcer of creditor
  interests; watchword became **"conditionality"**: no reforms, no money
- Mechanism: **structural adjustment programmes**
- **Washington Consensus** — ten-point wish-list: fiscal discipline,
  broadened tax base, lower rates, market-set interest and exchange
  rates, trade liberalization, capital flow liberalization
- "Hot money" — outlawed at Bretton Woods — was hot again

### John Perkins and the Neo-Imperialist Critique

- **John Perkins** (*Confessions of an Economic Hit Man*): claims he
  worked for Chas. T. Main, Inc. to ensure IMF/World Bank loans to
  Ecuador and Panama were spent on US-supplied goods

> "My real job . . . was giving loans to other countries, huge loans,
> much bigger than they could possibly repay . . . the country is left
> with debt plus lots of interest, and they basically become our
> servants, our slaves. It's a huge empire." — John Perkins

- Perkins claims **Jaime Roldós Aguilera** (Ecuador) and
  **Omar Torrijos** (Panama) were assassinated in 1981 for resisting
  this system
- Ferguson's pushback: US loans to Ecuador and Panama in the 1970s
  were only $96m and $197m respectively — less than 0.4% of total US
  grants and loans; Ecuador/Panama were minor US trading partners
- **Zoellick**: "The IMF and the World Bank lend money to countries
  in crisis, not countries that offer huge opportunities to corporate
  America."

### Stiglitz's Critique: More Credible

- **Joseph Stiglitz** (World Bank chief economist 1997–2000): IMF in
  1980s championed market supremacy with "ideological fervour" and
  took "a rather imperialistic view" of its role
- IMF's premature capital market liberalization "contributed to global
  instability . . . Jobs have been systematically destroyed"
- 1997 Asian crisis: IMF lent $95 billion but attached
  Washington Consensus conditions (higher rates, smaller deficits)
  that worsened the crisis — view echoed by **Paul Krugman**
- Ferguson's counter: capital liberalization in the 1980s was driven
  first by the **OECD**, then **European Commission** (French socialists
  **Jacques Delors** and **Michel Camdessus**) — arguably a
  "Paris Consensus" before a Washington Consensus
- **Margaret Thatcher** pursued unilateral capital account liberalization
  without US prompting; Reagan followed Thatcher's lead
- **Kenneth Rogoff** (IMF chief economist post-Asia crisis) in open
  letter to Stiglitz: governments come to the IMF when they can't find
  buyers for their debt and their currency is falling — printing more
  money in that situation causes inflation, not recovery
- East Asian economies (Indonesia, Malaysia, South Korea, Thailand)
  all returned swiftly to rapid growth after 1998 — no Depression
  materialized (except arguably Japan, which could hardly be blamed
  on IMF)

---

### The New Economic Hit Men: Hedge Funds

- 1980s: a different kind of "hit man" emerged — one who made a
  billion dollars on a single speculation, with no loyalty to any
  country and no need for violence
- These men ran **hedge funds**: lightly regulated, highly mobile,
  entirely private pools of capital — the return of hot money after
  the Bretton Woods deep freeze

### George Soros and Reflexivity

- **George Soros**: Hungarian-born, educated in London, emigrated to
  US 1956; built reputation at **Arnhold & S. Bleichroeder** (descended
  from the Berlin bank that managed Bismarck's money)
- Named his fund the **Quantum Fund** in honor of physicist
  **Werner Heisenberg**'s Uncertainty Principle
- Core theory: **reflexivity** — financial markets cannot be perfectly
  efficient because prices reflect the ignorance and biases of millions
  of investors; those biases then shape the events that markets are
  supposedly predicting

> "markets never reach the equilibrium postulated by economic theory.
> There is a two-way reflexive connection between perception and
> reality which can give rise to initially self-reinforcing but
> eventually self-defeating boom-bust processes, or bubbles. Every
> bubble consists of a trend and a misconception that interact in a
> reflexive manner." — Soros

- Intellectual lineage: philosopher **Karl Popper** (early influence,
  cited in *The Alchemy of Finance*, 1987)
- Soros's track record: long real estate 1969, bank stocks 1972,
  Japan 1971, oil 1972, defence stocks (deduced from Israeli complaints
  about US hardware in Yom Kippur War), short Western Union 1985,
  short the dollar (Plaza Accord, September 1985 — fund grew 122%)

### Black Wednesday: Soros Breaks the Bank of England

- Soros reasoned: German reunification costs would drive up
  Bundesbank interest rates → Deutschmark would rise → Britain's
  policy of shadowing the DM within the **European Exchange Rate
  Mechanism (ERM)** (joined 1990) was untenable as UK economy tanked
- Bet: borrowed **$10 billion** in sterling, invested in German
  currency at ~2.95 DM/£
- **16 September 1992 ("Black Wednesday")**: Britain withdrew from
  the ERM; sterling slumped 20%; Soros repaid borrowed sterling at
  the new lower rate and pocketed the difference
- Profit: **>$1 billion** — just 40% of that year's total profits
- Ferguson's personal anecdote: was a junior lecturer at Cambridge
  moonlighting as a newspaper leader writer; was certain Soros would
  win ("simple arithmetic: a trillion dollars traded daily vs. the
  Bank's meagre reserves")
- Key difference between old and new economic hit men: (1) no loyalty
  to any country, (2) sheer scale — Soros to partner
  **Stanley Druckenmiller**: "One billion dollars? You call that a
  position?"
- **Quantum Fund** returns: $100,000 invested in 1969 (Double Eagle,
  later Quantum) → $130 million by 1994; average annual growth 35%
- Technique: borrowing from investment banks to take leveraged long/
  short positions far exceeding the fund's own capital

### Limits of the Hedge Fund Model

- Soros's instincts (sometimes signaled by "a spasm of back pain")
  could be wrong; reflexivity is a special case, not a permanent rule
- This raised the question: could gut instinct be replaced by
  mathematics? Could there be an algebraic formula for double-digit
  returns?

---

## Section: Short-Term Capital Mismanagement

### Black-Scholes and the Dream of Mathematical Certainty

- Setup: imagine a planet of perfectly rational, omniscient investors
  where markets are continuous and frictionless — stock returns would
  follow a **random walk** and be normally distributed; a
  "six standard deviation" event would occur only once in four
  million years of trading
- **Myron Scholes** (Stanford), working with **Fisher Black** (Goldman
  Sachs), developed the **Black-Scholes model** — a revolutionary
  formula for pricing options
- Third collaborator: **Robert Merton** (Harvard Business School)
- Black-Scholes option price (C) depends on five variables:
  - S = current stock price
  - X = agreed future exercise price
  - T = expiration date
  - r = risk-free rate of return
  - σ = expected annual volatility of the stock
- To exploit the model required: markets full of people pricing
  options by gut feel, massive computing power (available since early
  1980s), and a partner with market savvy
- **Fisher Black** struck down by cancer; **John Meriwether**
  (former head of bond arbitrage at Salomon Brothers, made fortune
  from S&L crisis) became the market partner
- 1994: **Long-Term Capital Management (LTCM)** founded in Greenwich,
  Connecticut

### LTCM's Team and Early Success

- Dream team: Scholes + Merton (both future Nobel laureates) +
  Meriwether + former Fed vice-chairman **David Mullins** +
  ex-Harvard professor **Eric Rosenfeld** + ex-Salomon traders
  (Victor Haghani, Larry Hilibrand, Hans Hufschmid)
- Investors included **Merrill Lynch**, **Julius Baer**, **UBS**
- Minimum investment: $10 million; fees: 2% of assets + 25% of profits
- Investors locked in for 3 years; **Bear Stearns** executed trades
- First two years: returns of 43% and 41% after fees
- $10 million invested March 1994 → $40+ million by 1997
- By September 1997: net capital $6.7 billion; partners' stakes up
  10x
- The catch: to generate those returns LTCM had to borrow heavily
- August 1997: capital $6.7 billion; **debt-financed assets $126.4
  billion** — leverage ratio 19:1; by April 1998: $134 billion
- Models said this was safe: ~100 uncorrelated trading strategies,
  7,600 different positions — diversification meant all bets could
  not go wrong simultaneously

<!-- pp. 281-300 -->

## Chapter 6 (continued): LTCM Collapse & Aftermath

### LTCM's Core Strategy and Fatal Bet

- **Harry M. Markowitz** (Rand Corporation) and **William Sharpe's CAPM** — the
  theoretical foundations LTCM exploited
- LTCM exploited **pricing anomalies** across mortgage markets, government bonds,
  interest rate swaps — any market where two fundamentally identical assets had
  fractionally different prices
- Biggest bet: selling long-dated options on US and European stock markets —
  essentially betting volatility would revert to its recent average of 10-13%
- Options implied ~22% future volatility; LTCM sold them cheap, pocketing the
  spread — earned the nickname **"Central Bank of Volatility"**
- At peak: $40 million riding on each percentage point change in US equity volatility
- Claimed to be **market neutral** — "dynamic hedging" allowed selling options on
  an index while avoiding exposure to the index itself
- Paradox: partners worried they weren't taking *enough* risk; operating at
  ~10% annual variation when target was 20%
- **Value at Risk (VaR)** models said a ten-sigma event (losing all capital in
  a year) had probability of 1 in 10²⁴ — effectively zero
- Models built on only *five years* of data — missing the 1987 crash (11 years back)
  and the last great Russian default after the 1917 Revolution (80 years back)

### The Nobel Prize and the Beginning of the End

- October 1997: **Merton and Scholes** awarded the Nobel Prize in Economics
- December 31, 1997: LTCM returned $2.7 billion to outside investors, preferring
  to invest their own money — peak arrogance
- May 1998: equity markets dipped, volatility spiked to 27 (double the Long-Term
  projection) — fund dropped 6.7%; June down 10.1%; leverage hit 31:1

### The Asteroid Strikes

- July 1998: **Salomon Smith Barney** closed its US bond arbitrage group —
  the outfit virtually replicating LTCM's strategies; spooked markets
- **August 17, 1998**: Russia defaulted on its rouble-denominated domestic bonds
  — credit spreads exploded, equity volatility hit 29%, peaked at 45%
  (implying 3% daily index moves for five years)
- **Friday August 21, 1998**: LTCM lost $550 million — 15% of all capital —
  in a single day; leverage soared to 42:1
- All markets moved in sync, **correlations went to 1**, nullifying diversification
- End of August: down 44%; total loss over $1.8 billion

> 'John, you were the correlation.' — London hedge fund manager to Meriwether

### The Rescue

- **John Meriwether** flew back from Beijing; tried **Warren Buffett** (who had
  been recently shorted by LTCM — he declined)
- August 24: reluctantly sought **George Soros** — "the ultimate humiliation:
  quants from Planet Finance begging a bail-out from the earthling prophet of
  irrational, unquantifiable reflexivity"
- Soros offered $500m contingent on finding another $500m — it fell through
- Other banks scented blood and wanted collateral, not rescue
- **Federal Reserve Bank of New York** brokered a $3.625 billion bail-out by
  fourteen Wall Street banks
- Original investors (including those same banks, plus University of Pittsburgh)
  saw holdings fall from $4.9 billion to $400 million
- Sixteen partners left with $30 million between them

### Why LTCM Failed: The Diagnosis

- **Black-Scholes assumptions**: markets efficient, continuous, frictionless,
  liquid; returns follow a normal bell-curve distribution
- Reality: in a crisis, participants *withdraw* from markets, leaving an illiquid
  portfolio that can't be sold at any price
- Many firms had copied LTCM's strategies — when things went wrong, it was as if
  an entire "super-portfolio" was hemorrhaging; herd stampede for exits
- **VaR models used only five years of data** — missed 1987 crash, missed 1917
  Russian default; calibrated to a world that no longer existed

> 'If I had lived through the Depression, I would have been in a better position
> to understand events.' — **John Meriwether**

> 'The Nobel prize winners had known plenty of mathematics, but not enough
> history. They had understood the beautiful theory of Planet Finance, but
> overlooked the messy past of Planet Earth.' — Ferguson's summary

- **Myron Scholes**: 'Maybe the error of Long Term was . . . that of not
  realizing that the world is becoming more and more global over time.'
- Meriwether: 'The nature of the world had changed, and we hadn't recognized it.'
- Final verdict: **Long-Term Capital Management** ended up being
  **Short-Term Capital Mismanagement**

### The Hedge Fund Explosion Post-LTCM

- Contrary to expectations, quant hedge funds didn't vanish after 1998
- Of 1,308 hedge funds formed 1989–1996, over a third (36.7%) had ceased to
  exist by end of that period; average lifespan just 40 months
- Yet assets exploded: 600 funds / $39bn (1990) → 3,873 / $490bn (2000)
  → 7,601 / $1.9 trillion (Q1 2008)
- Pension funds and university endowments now investing alongside "high net
  worth" individuals — broadening the investor base dramatically
- Returns falling: 18% in the 1990s → 7.5% (2000–2006); growing scepticism
  that returns reflect **alpha** (skill) vs. **beta** (market exposure)
- Top managers' 2007 earnings: **John Paulson** $3.7bn (subprime bets),
  **George Soros** $2.9bn, **Ken Griffin** (Citadel), **James Simons** (Renaissance)
- **John Kay's point**: if Buffett had charged "2 and 20," he would have kept
  $57bn of the $62bn Berkshire made for shareholders over 42 years

### The "Bogus Hedge Fund" Template

Ferguson outlines a step-by-step scam strategy exploiting the fee structure:
1. Park $100m in T-bills at 4%
2. Sell 100m covered options (10c on dollar) paying out if S&P falls >20%
3. Reinvest the $10m proceeds to sell more options, netting another $1m
4. Earn $11m from options + 4% on $110m T-bills = **15.4% return**
5. Collect 2% management fee + 20% of performance above 4% benchmark = ~$4m
6. 60% chance this runs >5 years without triggering the options = $15m profit
- Conclusion: **counterparty risk** and misaligned incentives created a
  systemic threat larger than 1998 — the LTCM crisis waiting to happen again,
  at greater scale

---

## "Chimerica" (Epilogue/Coda Section)

### The China Paradox

- The "mystery years" post-2000: markets boomed despite rising short-term rates,
  glaring trade imbalances, and soaring political risk — the paradox resolved
  by **China**
- **Chongqing** (32m people, deep inland): embodiment of China's transformation
  — mix of Communist-planned infrastructure and unfettered private enterprise
- **Wu Yajun** (property developer, $9bn net worth) and **Yin Mingsha**
  (Lifan motorcycles, 1.5m units/year) — 345,000+ dollar millionaires now in China
- China avoided the emerging market crises of 1997-8 by:
  - Devaluing renminbi in 1994, retaining **capital controls**
  - Requiring foreign capital as **direct investment** (factories, not hot money)
  - Financing growth primarily from **domestic savings** and overseas Chinese diaspora

### The Capital Flow Reversal

- Chinese households save an unusually high proportion of income; corporations
  save even more — in contrast to Americans who saved almost nothing
- 2007: US needed to borrow ~$800bn from rest of world ($4bn+ every working day)
- China ran a $262bn current account surplus — more than a quarter of the US deficit
- **"The People's Republic of China has become banker to the United States"**
- Mechanism: China bought dollars to prevent renminbi appreciation, recycling
  export earnings into **US Treasury and government agency bonds** —
  some called this **"Bretton Woods II"**
- By 2006, Chinese dollar holdings almost certainly exceeded $1 trillion

### Chimerica: The Symbiosis

> 'Welcome to the wonderful dual country of "Chimerica" — China plus America —
> which accounts for just over a tenth of the world's land surface, a quarter of
> its population, a third of its economic output and more than half of global
> economic growth in the past eight years.'

- **East Chimericans** saved; **West Chimericans** spent
- Chinese imports kept down US inflation; Chinese savings kept down US interest rates;
  Chinese labour kept down US wage costs
- **Ben Bernanke's "savings glut"** — Chimerica was the underlying cause of:
  - The surge in bank lending, bond issuance, and derivative contracts
  - The hedge fund population explosion
  - Private equity leveraged buyouts
  - The US mortgage market awash with cash (100% mortgages, no income/job required)
- Global real interest rates fell more than a third below their 15-year average;
  US corporate profits in 2006 rose by about the same proportion above their
  GDP share — all courtesy of Chimerica

### The Fragility of Chimerica

- The **subprime mortgage crisis of 2007** was predictable; what wasn't was how
  defaults in America's "home-grown emerging market" would seize up interbank
  lending worldwide, destroy CDO values, and cause the first UK bank run since
  1866 (Northern Rock, nationalized)
- As of May 2008, a US recession seemed underway — but not the end of the world
- **Sovereign wealth funds** (SWFs) by end of 2007: ~$2.6 trillion under
  management — more than all hedge funds; could reach $27 trillion within
  15 years (Morgan Stanley forecast)
- Asian and Middle Eastern SWFs invested in Barclays, Bear Stearns, Citigroup,
  Merrill Lynch, Morgan Stanley, UBS, Blackstone, Carlyle
- Irony: among the biggest winners of the Western financial crisis were
  **state-owned entities** — an anomaly for "market fundamentalism" advocates
- Tensions: US dollar depreciated ~25% since 2007 crisis; China accused of
  currency manipulation while US own rate cuts/facilities were doing the same
- The Chimerica analogy to 1914: then it was **Britain–Germany** symbiosis
  that fractured into catastrophe; could US–China follow the same path?

> 'Maybe, as its name was always intended to hint, Chimerica is nothing more
> than a chimera — the mythical beast of ancient legend that was part lion,
> part goat, part dragon.'

### Three Lessons of Financial History

1. Major wars can arise even when economic globalization is advanced and an
   English-speaking empire seems secure
2. The longer the world goes without major conflict, the harder one becomes to
   imagine (and perhaps the easier to start)
3. Crises cause much more disruption when they strike complacent investors than
   battle-scarred ones — the really big crises come just seldom enough to be
   beyond living memory

- **Average Wall Street CEO career: just over 25 years** — first-hand memories
  don't extend back beyond 1983, ten years after the last great surge in oil
  and gold prices
- "That fact alone provides a powerful justification for the study of financial history."

---

## Afterword: The Descent of Money

### The Four-Millennium Summary

- Money (crystallized debtor-creditor relationship) → banks → bond markets
  (13th c.) → stock markets (17th c.) → insurance/pension funds (18th c.)
  → futures/options/derivatives (19th c.) → leveraged real estate democracy (20th c.)
- Economies combining all these institutions outperformed those that didn't —
  financial intermediation allocates resources more efficiently than feudalism
  or central planning
- Western financial model spread via imperialism, then globalization
- **Frederic Mishkin** (Fed Governor): 'the financial system [is] the brain
  of the economy . . . If capital goes to the wrong uses or does not flow at
  all, the economy will operate inefficiently.'

### Three Reasons for Inherent Instability

**1. Radical Uncertainty (not just calculable risk)**
- **Frank Knight** (1921): distinction between *measurable* risk and
  *unmeasurable* uncertainty — much of life involves unique events where
  no probability can be calculated
- **Keynes** (1937, response to critics of *General Theory*): "uncertain
  knowledge" means not merely probable but unknowable — e.g., the rate of
  interest twenty years hence; "we simply do not know"
- Keynes's three investor coping mechanisms: (1) assume present is guide to
  future; (2) assume existing prices correctly sum up future prospects;
  (3) conform to majority behaviour ("wisdom of crowds")

**2. Human Behavioural Biases**
- **Daniel Kahneman and Amos Tversky**: experiments showing systematic
  miscalculation — people are **risk-averse for gains, risk-seeking for losses**
- A loss has ~2.5x the psychological impact of an equivalent gain
- Ten identified **heuristic biases** (cognitive traps):
  1. *Availability bias* — rely on readily available memory, not needed data
  2. *Hindsight bias* — overestimate ex-post probability of past events
  3. *Problem of induction* — generalize from insufficient data
  4. *Fallacy of conjunction* — overestimate probability all 7 events at
     90% will occur; underestimate that at least one 10% event will occur
  5. *Confirmation bias* — seek confirming evidence, ignore falsifying
  6. *Contamination effects* — irrelevant proximate info influences decisions
  7. *Affect heuristic* — preconceived value-judgements warp cost-benefit
  8. *Scope neglect* — can't scale willingness-to-sacrifice proportionally
  9. *Overconfidence in calibration* — conflate "best case" with "most probable"
  10. *Bystander apathy* — abdicate responsibility in crowds
- **Behavioural finance** may be the field most likely to revolutionize our
  understanding of markets; the efficient markets hypothesis is under serious challenge

**3. Evolutionary/Darwinian Dynamics** (introduced at end of this section)
- **Andrew Lo** (MIT Lab for Financial Engineering): re-conceptualizing
  markets as adaptive systems — evolutionary forces as real in finance as
  in nature
- **Thorstein Veblen** first asked "Why is Economics Not an Evolutionary
  Science?" — evolutionary economics is now a well-established sub-discipline

<!-- pp. 301-320 -->

## Conclusion: The Descent of Finance (continued)

### Creative Destruction in Finance

- **Joseph Schumpeter** in *Capitalism, Socialism and Democracy*:
  capitalism driven not by external shocks but by internal mutation —
  new goods, new methods, new markets, new organizational forms
- The "fundamental impulse" keeps capitalism in motion by
  *incessantly destroying the old* and creating the new

> "This process of Creative Destruction is the essential fact about capitalism."
> — *Schumpeter*

- Scale of destruction in modern economy: ~1 in 10 US companies
  disappears each year; 1989–1997 avg 611,000 businesses/year vanished
  out of 5.73 million total
- Extinction rate can hit 20% in bad years
  (DC financial sector in 1989, at height of S&L crisis)
- UK: 30% of tax-registered businesses gone within 3 years
- Of the world's 100 largest companies in 1912:
  29 bankrupt by 1995, 48 disappeared, only 19 still in top 100
- **Banks don't fail as often only because governments explicitly and
  implicitly protect them from collapse** — a key distortion

### Six Features of Finance as Evolutionary System

Ferguson identifies six parallels between finance and biology:

1. **Genes** — business practices act as genetic material,
   stored in "organizational memory," passed firm to firm
2. **Mutation** — spontaneous innovation, primarily technological
3. **Competition** — firms compete for resources;
   longevity and proliferation determine which practices persist
4. **Natural selection** — market allocation of capital and labor;
   under-performance leads to death ("differential survival")
5. **Speciation** — wholly new types of financial institution emerge
6. **Extinction** — species die out altogether

- Financial history = result of **institutional mutation and
  natural selection**
- "Drift" (random innovations) and "flow" (adoption of foreign
  practices, e.g. US models spreading to Chinese banks) also play roles
- **Co-evolution** occurs: hedge funds and prime brokers evolve together
- Market selection is the main driver; organisms compete for
  finite resources

### Finance vs. Biology: Where the Analogy Breaks Down

- A 'good enough' mutation achieves dominance if it occurs at the
  right moment — initial slim advantage can translate into prolonged
  dominance (path dependence)
- Evolution is NOT progressive: primitive life-forms (loan sharks)
  are not condemned to oblivion any more than prokaryotes
- Evolved complexity does NOT protect against extinction
- Key difference: M&A in finance directly causes mutation
  (eating another firm transforms both)
- No financial equivalent to sexual reproduction
- Most financial mutation is **deliberate, conscious innovation** —
  more **Lamarckian than Darwinian** (firms adapt within their own
  lifetimes to observed change)
- **Rudolf Hilferding** (German socialist, ~90 years before writing)
  predicted inexorable concentration toward **finance capital**
- Conventional view: financial history moves toward consolidation
  (Citigroup's family tree tracing back to City Bank of NY, 1812)
- Ferguson's counter: financial history *begins* at a common trunk
  and **branches outward** — speciation, not consolidation,
  is the real story

### Biodiversity in Modern Finance

- Banking sector retains significant biodiversity:
  giants (Citigroup, Bank of America) coexist with
  fragmented regional and cooperative institutions
- Near-extinct species: **state-owned bank** (privatization swept
  the world; Northern Rock's nationalization hints at possible return)
- New species proliferating:
  - **Mono-line** financial services firms (e.g. **Capital One**)
  - Private banking boutiques
  - Direct/Internet banking
  - **Hedge funds** and **private equity** partnerships
  - **Sovereign wealth funds** (from exporters of goods and energy)
- New financial assets proliferating: mortgage-backed securities,
  other asset-backed securities, OTC derivatives
  (OTC derivatives: profitable for sellers but lack standardization,
  creating legal disputes in crises)
- Financial sector = a **twenty-year Cambrian explosion**:
  giants exist alongside and do not preclude smaller species

### Financial Crises as Mass Extinctions

- Evolutionary disruptions in finance = geopolitical shocks and
  financial crises
- Crucial difference from biology: asteroids are **exogenous**;
  financial crises are **endogenous** to the financial system
- Historical "mass extinctions": bank panics of the 1930s,
  S&L failures of the 1980s
- **Great Depression** (1930s) and **Great Inflation** (1970s) =
  major discontinuities
- 2007 credit crunch as potential new mass extinction:
  - Total losses on ABS and risky debt estimated >$1 trillion
  - As of May 2008: ~$318bn in write-downs acknowledged;
    $600bn+ still to come
  - Financial institutions raised ~$225bn new capital,
    shortfall ~$100bn
  - With capital/assets ratios <10%, balance sheets may need
    to shrink by ~$1 trillion
  - **Shadow banking system** (off-balance-sheet SIVs and conduits)
    makes contraction especially difficult
- Basel I and II capital adequacy accords under pressure:
  European average bank capital now ~4% of assets (was ~25% in
  early 20th century)
- **Bond insurance companies** likely to disappear;
  some hedge funds likely to thrive on return of volatility

> "As with past forest fires in the markets, we're likely to see
> incredible flora and fauna springing up in its wake."
> — **Andrew Lo**

### Regulation as "Intelligent Design"

- Evolution in finance occurs within a **regulatory framework** —
  unlike biology, "intelligent design" plays a real role
- Regulatory changes are endogenous: regulators are often
  former private sector participants ("poachers turned gamekeepers")
- Net effect analogous to **climate change** on biological evolution:
  new rules can make previously successful traits suddenly
  disadvantageous
- Rise and fall of **Savings and Loans** largely due to
  US regulatory environment changes
- The **"too big to fail"** problem: implicit bailout guarantees
  create **moral hazard**, encouraging excessive risk-taking
- From evolutionary perspective: TBTF institutions are
  *actively harmful* — without creative destruction,
  the evolutionary process is thwarted
- **Japan in the 1990s** as warning: propping up insolvent banks
  created an "economic dead hand" that suppressed growth for a decade
- Every shock *must* produce casualties for the system to adapt

> "This economic system cannot do without the *ultima ratio* of the
> complete destruction of those existences which are irretrievably
> associated with the hopelessly unadapted."
> — *Schumpeter* (on firms "unfit to live")

### Ferguson's Conclusion: The Mirror of Mankind

- The book's title *The Ascent of Money* may sound optimistically
  ironic in a time of dollar inflation and flight into commodities —
  but the long-run trajectory is unquestionably upward
- Allusion: title nods to **Jacob Bronowski**'s *Ascent of Man*
- Financial history has a **saw-tooth quality** — great reverses
  and crises — but no crash has set humanity permanently back
- Alternative title considered: *The Descent of Finance*
  (homage to Darwin) — because the story is authentically evolutionary
- Every mundane financial transaction (ATM withdrawal, bond
  investment, mortgage, international diversification) has
  deep historical antecedents
- Core thesis: financial markets are not a monster to be caged —
  they are **the mirror of mankind**, revealing how we value
  ourselves and the world's resources

> "financial markets are like the mirror of mankind, revealing
> every hour of every working day the way we value ourselves
> and the resources of the world around us. It is not the fault
> of the mirror if it reflects our blemishes as clearly as
> our beauty."
> — *Ferguson*

