<!-- pp. 461-473 -->

## Endnotes (pp. 461–473)

These pages are the book's endnotes section, lettered a through bm.
Many contain substantive facts, quotes, and elaborations omitted
from the main text. Key entries below.

---

### Finance, Gender & Retirement

- **(a)** The increase for female MBA graduates was from 2.3 to 3.4% —
  "the masters of the universe still outnumber the mistresses"
- **(b)** **401(k) plans** introduced in 1980 as defined-contribution
  retirement vehicles; employees defer wages into accounts with
  investment choices; no tax until withdrawal

---

### Historical Clarifications

- **(c)** Columbus's first settlement, **La Isabela** in Hispaniola,
  was established to exploit local gold; the only silver traces found
  were from ore samples Columbus had brought *from Spain*
- **(d)** "Spain" from 1474 to the 18th century was technically the
  union of two kingdoms: **Aragon** and **Castile**
- **(e)** The **Fibonacci sequence** first appeared under the name
  *matrameru* (mountain of cadence) in the work of Sanskrit scholar
  **Pingala** — not in *The Da Vinci Code* as most people assume

---

### Banking & Monetary Concepts

- **(f)** The Medici's *segreto* books recorded income, profits, and
  key contracts; other books: *libro di entrata e uscita*
  (income/expenditures) and *libro dei debitori e creditori*
  (debtors/creditors)
- **(g)** The Bank of England monopoly applied only within a
  65-mile radius of London; private banks could still issue notes
  in the 18th century
- **(h)** **Illiquidity** = right amount of assets, but not
  marketable (too few buyers). **Insolvency** = liabilities clearly
  exceed assets. Distinction harder to draw in practice — a firm in
  a liquidity crisis may sell assets only at prices that imply
  insolvency
- **(i)** Mortgage debt rose from 54% to **140% of disposable
  personal income** over the same period
- **(j)** **Marshallian k** (named after **Alfred Marshall**) =
  ratio of monetary base to nominal GDP

---

### Bond & Rothschild Notes

- **(k)** Current yield ≠ yield to maturity; the latter accounts for
  time until the bond is redeemed at par
- **(l)** Origin of the name **"consols"** — new standardized
  British government bonds
- **(m)** **Nathan Rothschild** letter to Prussian Treasury Director
  **Christian Rother**, after Rother tried to renegotiate loan
  terms post-signing:

> 'Dearest friend, I have now done my duty by God, your king and
> the Finance Minister von Rother, my money has all gone to you in
> Berlin . . . the cabal has only impotence and the King of Prussia
> . . . should be well pleased and thank Rothschild, who is sending
> you so much money [and] raising Prussia's credit.'
> — *Nathan Rothschild*

  Ferguson notes: "That a Jew born in the Frankfurt ghetto could
  write in these terms to a Prussian official speaks volumes about
  the social revolution Nathan Rothschild and his brothers
  personified."

---

### Anti-Semitism & Finance

- **(n)** **J. A. Hobson**, author of *Imperialism: A Study* (1902),
  articulated classically anti-Semitic hostility toward finance,
  claiming that banking, broking, and loan-floating form "the
  central ganglion of international capitalism," controlled
  "chiefly by men of a single and peculiar race"

---

### Inflation & Money Supply

- **(o)** Quantity theory of money: **MV = PQ** where M = money
  supply, V = velocity, P = price level, Q = real value of
  transactions
- **(p)** **Preobrazhensky** (Bolshevik economist who theorized
  "euthanasia of money") was in fact most directly implicated in
  the execution of **Nicholas II** and his family — "murder rather
  than euthanasia was his forte"
- **(q)** Highest recorded inflation in history: **Hungary, July
  1946** — prices rose 4.19 quintillion per cent (419 followed by
  16 zeros)
- **(r)** As of March 2008 (writing), a funeral in **Zimbabwe**
  cost 1 billion Zimbabwean dollars; annual inflation 100,000%
- **(s)** Long-run average P/E ratio (US, since 1871): **15.5x**;
  peak in 1999: 32.6x; at time of writing: 18.6x
  (S&P 500, via Global Financial Data)

---

### Dutch & Bubble History

- **(t)** Between 1580 and 1640 the crowns of Spain and Portugal
  were united
- **(u)** Removing dividend uncertainty gave VOC shares the
  character of preference shares or bonds
- **(v)** **Bank of Amsterdam** success: consumer price inflation
  fell from 2% p.a. (1550–1608) → 0.9% (1609–1658) → 0.1%
  (1659–1779); VOC stock's ~8-fold appreciation compares well
  with inflation-adjusted modern equity returns
- **(w)** Traces of Acadian survivors still found in Louisiana
  parishes of St Charles, St James, and St John the Baptist
- **(x)** **Bubble Act** made it illegal to form new companies
  without statutory authority and barred existing companies from
  activities not in their charters

---

### Federal Reserve & Greenspan

- **(y)** The **federal funds rate** = rate banks charge each other
  for overnight balances held at the Fed; set by the **Federal Open
  Market Committee** (7 governors + 12 regional bank presidents);
  implemented by the NY Fed via open market operations
- **(z)** Greenspan's famous 1996 "irrational exuberance" speech
  was characteristically opaque:

> 'Clearly, sustained low inflation implies less uncertainty about
> the future . . . But how do we know when irrational exuberance
> has unduly escalated asset values . . . ? We as central bankers
> need not be concerned if a collapsing financial asset bubble does
> not threaten to impair the real economy.'
> — *Alan Greenspan*

- **(aa)** Enron was originally going to be named **Enteron** until
  the *Wall Street Journal* noted 'enteron' is Greek for intestines

---

### Insurance Footnotes

- **(ab)** Gulf Coast homeowner hurricane policies typically exclude
  "Water Damage" (flood, tidal water, tsunami, seiche) — classic
  small print designed to limit insurer liability in ways
  "not readily intelligible to the policyholder"
- **(ac)** US property/casualty insurers had net after-tax income
  of $43bn in 2005 and $64bn in 2006, vs. avg <$24bn in
  prior three years — Katrina ultimately *enriched* the industry
- **(ad)** **Dickie Scruggs** bribery scandal: associate
  **Timothy Balducci** taped offering $40,000 to Judge Lackey;
  referenced "bodies buried" over 5-6 years of dealings
- **(af)** Classic pattern of post-disaster reform:
  fire insurance reserve requirements came *after* the
  1835 New York fire; **reinsurance** developed *after* the
  1842 Hamburg fire
- **(ag)** **Robert Wallace** (Scottish actuary, co-founder of
  Scottish Widows precursor) was also a member of the
  Philosophical Society of Edinburgh and anticipated Malthus's
  *Essay on the Principle of Population*
- **(ah)** **Sir Walter Scott** was ruined by the 1825 Latin
  American debt crisis — a sleeping partner in printers
  **Ballantyne & Co.** and publisher **Archibald Constable**,
  left with debts of £117,000–£130,000; vowed to write his
  way back to solvency rather than sell Abbotsford; succeeded
  but died in 1832 of the effort

---

### Real Estate & Mortgages

- **(al)** House prices in England rose **15-fold** between 1975
  and 2006, putting homeownership out of reach for most
  first-time buyers without parental assistance
- **(am)** Homeownership rates (c. 2000): Ireland 83%, Australia
  69%, UK 69%, Canada 67%, US 65%, Japan 60%, France 54%,
  Germany 43%; US has since risen above 68%
- **(ao)** ~37 million Americans claim the mortgage interest
  deduction on loans up to $1,000,000 — costs $76bn to
  the US Treasury annually
- **(ap)** Key S&L deregulation legislation: **Depository
  Institutions Deregulation and Monetary Control Act (1980)**
  and **Garn–St Germain Depository Institutions Act (1982)**
- **(aq)** Most notorious S&L scandal: **Charles Keating**,
  whose Lincoln Savings & Loan received support from five
  Senators including **John McCain** (later cleared by the
  Senate Ethics Committee)
- **(ar)** End of 2006 mortgage market share: GSEs 30%;
  commercial banks 22%; RMBS/CDOs/ABS 14%; savings
  institutions 13%; state/local governments 8%;
  life insurers 6%
- **(at)** Between 1997–2006, US consumers withdrew an
  estimated **$9 trillion** in cash from home equity;
  by Q1 2006, home equity extraction = ~10% of
  disposable personal income
- **(au)** In many US states, mortgages are **"no recourse"**
  loans — lender can only seize the property, not other
  assets or future wages; creates strong incentive to default

---

### Hedge Funds & Derivatives

- **(bd)** Term "hedge fund" first used in 1966 for the
  long-short fund set up by **Alfred Winslow Jones** in 1949;
  as limited liability partnerships, hedge funds are exempt
  from the 1933 Securities Act and 1940 Investment Company Act
- **(bf)** **Swap** = derivative where one party pays fixed
  interest, the other pays floating (typically **LIBOR**),
  applied to a notional amount
- **(bh)** "It is surely no coincidence that it was reports of
  losses at hedge funds run by **Bear Stearns** and by
  **Goldman Sachs** that signalled the onset of the credit
  crunch in the summer of 2007"

---

### Emerging Markets & Geopolitics

- **(az)** Term "**emerging markets**" first coined in the 1980s
  by World Bank economist **Antoine van Agtmael**
- **(ba)** Marshall Plan total = ~5.4% of US GNP in 1948, or
  1.1% spread over the full program (April 1948–June 1952);
  an equivalent plan 2003–2007 would have cost $550bn;
  actual Bush-era foreign aid 2001–2006 was <$150bn
  (<0.2% of GDP)
- **(bb)** **Walt Rostow**, author of *The Stages of Economic
  Growth: A Non-Communist Manifesto* (1960), was NSA to LBJ
  and closely associated with Vietnam War escalation
- **(bc)** **Washington Consensus** (10 points, Williamson 1989):
  fiscal discipline; tax reform; liberalize interest rates;
  health/education spending; property rights; privatization;
  deregulate markets; competitive exchange rate; free trade;
  open to FDI
- **(bg)** JP Morgan EM bond spread over Treasuries:
  3.3% (Oct 1997) → 6.6% (Jul 1998) → **17.05%**
  (10 Sep 1998) — scale of LTCM-era emerging market panic

---

### Sovereign Wealth Funds

- **(bi)** Sovereign wealth funds have longer history than assumed:
  **Kuwait Investment Authority** (1953), **Singapore Temasek**
  (1974), **ADIA** UAE (1976), **Singapore GIC** (1981)
- China Investment Corporation chairman **Lou Jiwei** on
  buying 9.9% of Morgan Stanley for $5bn in Dec 2007:
  "If we see a big fat rabbit, we will shoot at it" —
  then added, "Some people may say we were shot by
  Morgan Stanley"

---

### Risk, History & Capital Regulation

- **(bk)** **Peter Bernstein**: "We pour in data from the past . . .
  but past data . . . constitute a sequence of events rather than
  a set of independent observations . . . History provides us with
  only one sample of the . . . capital markets, not with thousands
  of separate and randomly distributed numbers"
- **(bl)** **Basel I** (1988): banks hold 8% capital against
  risk-weighted assets; **Basel II** (2004): adds operational
  and market risk, mandates **VaR** models; liquidity risk
  classified as mere "residual risk" — ironic given 2007–8;
  rules inherently conflict with banks' incentive to minimize
  capital and maximize ROE
- **(bm)** **Andrew Lo**: "Hedge funds are the Galapagos Islands
  of finance . . . The rate of innovation, evolution, competition,
  adaptation, births and deaths . . . occurs at an extraordinarily
  rapid clip"

